[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ It's very hard to plan for an intro chapter for a course that aims to cover the entirety of the opening theory bar 1.e4 @@StartBracket@@and, oddly, considering it's called Peter Svidler's Grünfeld, the Grünfeld itself − see Part 1!@@EndBracket@@.  What I can do is give you an idea of what the course contains in terms of Black's options, and talk a little bit about the ideology behind those choices.  I can't promise I stayed true to that shining ideal for every single line against every single White's option on move 1, of course − but just as with the Grünfeld, my biggest priority when building a Black repertoire for myself has always been, if I had to choose one word: 'playability', certainly not 'equality' anyway. The margins in chess are narrow enough that I definitely believe that in most cases, those two things can coexist quite easily.   Whenever there's a choice, I gravitate towards lines that promise sharp, dynamic, unclear positions over the lines that offer more efficient, but less exciting, equilibrium. I hope you'll enjoy this approach and now it's time to talk about the variations a little bit. }
1. Nf3
{ This, in my mind, is the End Boss of Anti-Grünfeld. White preserves pretty much all of their options while taking the one we want the most away from us.   A@@EndBracket@@ The English Opening is of course a very serious topic:  1.c4  .  Here, I stayed largely true to my recommendations from the old chess24 course.  1...g6  2.Nc3   2.e4  e5  3.d4  Nf6  still holds, with some refinements from the last time.  2...c5  3.g3  Bg7  4.Bg2  Nc6  and in this symmetrical line, White's right of the first move means we have to be careful, but I believe my choice of  5.Nf3  e6!?  is a good mix of solidity and exciting counterplay.   B@@EndBracket@@ And then we come to  1.d4  Nf6  2.Bf4  .  Other moves are also covered, of course, but the biggest challenge I faced was to finally study and get a sense of, the London.  2...g6  3.Nf3  Bg7  .  I spent many hours nailing down our reactions to all the little move orders White can choose here, and in the end, I believe I will present to you a streamlined and understandable concept of how not to get too bogged down, and whenever possible go for sharp and unbalanced positions. }
1... Nf6
{ For the vast majority of my career, I replied to 1.Nf3 by playing 1...Nf6. }
2. c4
{ And in this position, choosing between the text move or  2...c5  3.Nc3  d5  . }
2... g6 3. Nc3
{ And here, I used to play  3...d5  4.cxd5  Nxd5  almost exclusively for many years but recently, having any kind of fun in that line became quite hard due to how well-honed  5.h4  is in skillful hands. This is why we're going to do something else entirely. }
3... Bg7 4. e4 e5
{ I wasn't going to abandon you to the KID, of course. Having said that, in the KID we wouldn't be a pawn down by move five. }
5. Nxe5 O-O
{ I think this modern gambit offers Black the type of play that I have described above, and hope you will enjoy what this course has to offer. Let's take the leap!  Peter Svidler  St. Petersburg, January 2022 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide 1.Nf3"]
[Black "Symmetrical Grünfeld 6.O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
{ This is a very serious move, of course. In many cases White will have the option of transposing into the Grünfeld later on if we decide to play ...Nf6 and ...g6 here, as we will. But in this volume we'll be dealing with the options White can choose that don't allow us to play our beloved opening. }
1... Nf6 2. c4
{ 2.d4  g6  transposes to various other lines, depending on White's next move. }
2... g6 3. Nc3 Bg7
{ 3...d5  has been my move of choice for many years, but I'm not quite happy enough with  4.cxd5  Nxd5  , and now, to the surprise of absolutely nobody in the 2020s,  5.h4!? }
4. g3
{ There are a lot of transpositions when we're discussing the Nf3/c4/g3 lines, and I'm making this move order the main one because it's the only one that really properly discourages Black from going back to the ...c6/...d5 systems in reply − and because this move order exists, I will not be recommending ...c6/...d5 anywhere else, either.   The point is that with the knight already on c3,  4...c6  can and should be met by  5.e4  , and we're not going to get back to the symmetrical Grünfeld positions we've discussed in Part 1 of this LTR. }
4... O-O 5. Bg2 c5
{ We avoid the Grünfeld-type move  5...d5  , as  6.cxd5  Nxd5  7.h4!  is, once again, bothering. }
6. O-O d5
{ Now that White no longer has any of those scary h4 ideas, we're ready to commit to ...d5. }
7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Qb3
{ Not very critical and it allows us a very nice Maroczy setup. } 8... Nc7 9.
Qc4 { Or  9.d3  Nc6  10.Be3  b6  which is similar to the main line. } 9... Ne6
10. d3 Nc6
{ And we're already quite happy with things. Our plan is to play ...b6, either immediately or after preparing it with ...Rb8 or ...Bd7, and then use the d4-square as a very nice base of operations. Playing e3 to stop that results in White acquiring a weakness on d3, which we also don’t mind at all. }
*

