13... b6
{ I like this forcing line the most.   13...Qe6!?  14.Qxc5  Qxa2  is also fine while @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/pp2pp1p/2n1qbp1/1Qp5/8/3PBNP1/P3PPBP/1R3RK1 w - - 6 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Qa4  gives us an option of repeating with  14...Qd7  or looking for more. }
14. Nd2 { It's the same with Ng5. } 14... Bb7 15. Ne4 Rab8
{ Preventing Nxc5 is much more important than avoiding the trade of Bf6. } 16.
Bf4 { 16.Nxf6+  exf6  is just an extra pawn for us. } 16... Qc8 17. Bxb8 Nd4
18. Nxf6+ { 18.Qb2?  Nf3+  and the queen is lost. } 18... exf6 19. Qb2 Bxg2 20.
Kxg2 Qc6+ 21. f3 Rxb8
{ Black had excellent compensation for the exchange in Jakovenko-Cheparinov, Poikovsky 2013. }
