5... O-O
{ In the past, people were connecting this move order with the understandable idea of not being a pawn down before they even drew a breath, and winning it back straight away with  5...Nxe4  . However, the position after  6.Nxe4  Bxe5  7.d4  Bg7  8.Bg5!  f6  9.Be3  while not unplayable, is definitely not something I would recommend.  Our compensation is of course based on the tempi we will win chasing the  Ne5  back, and the open e-file. We're also threatening  ...Nxe4  here. However, White hasn't really sinned against the chess principles too much in the four developing moves that were made so far, and the one capture − meaning we can't expect an easy ride. White has a number of viable options: }
6. Nf3
{ White removes the knight from its vulnerable post in an attempt to hold on to the e4-pawn. After  6...Re8  , there are three major ways to do so and we will deal with all of them independently. }
6... Re8 7. Bd3 { This is a very serious option. } 7... Nxe4
{ Sadly, we have to make this choice over the much more exciting  7...d5  , which has been played recently by very strong players, including Mamedyarov and Fedoseev. }
8. Bxe4 Bxc3 9. dxc3 Rxe4+ 10. Be3 Nc6
{ More precise than  10...d6  which allows  11.c5  . We don't want to be playing  11...d5  since it weakens our dark squares even further and makes the d4-square into an absolute stronghold for White.  We would, of course, prefer our pawn could go back to g7, but even as it is, the fact that there is only one open file, and we can expect a lot of trading down the e-file once both sides have developed, makes me think this is nowhere near as bad as one might suspect. }
11. O-O { 11.Qd2  d6  12.O-O  Bf5  transposes into the main line. } 11... d6
12. Qd2 Bf5
{ Our development will always look like this if we’re undisturbed, and we’re never ever considering spending a tempo on the c4-pawn. }
13. b3 Qe7 14. h3 Re8 15. Ng5 Re5
{ We're in firm control of the e-file, making our position safe. } *

