1. c4
{ The English is easily a topic for a full LTR, but I'll try to show you a way to cut down on the number of options White can choose against us. }
1... g6
{ Just as all those years ago, I'm recommending this somewhat rare move as a reply. In most cases, we will transpose back into classical English setups, but by choosing this move, we're locking White out of some of the lines they could try forcing on us. }
2. e4 e5
{ Another important point − we're not planning to be forced into playing the King's Indian, that should always be a choice you make of your own free will. }
3. Nf3 { White allows us to get a better grip on the center by normal means. }
3... Bg7 4. d4
{ I had an online game against Nepomniachtchi who played  4.Nc3  instead, which I believe to be inaccurate in view of  4...Nc6  ,  stopping d4 for the time being. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6
{ I will note that  5...Nc6  6.Nxc6  bxc6  is also entirely playable, but I like the text move better since it allows us to engage White in an immediate fight in the center.   Our plan will be to castle and then push for ...c6 and ...d5 @@StartBracket@@and in many cases, actually ...d5! followed by ...c6 once White takes@@EndBracket@@ in order to save a tempo on ...d7-d6 altogether. }
6. Nc3
{ 6.e5?!  Ne4  is  not great for White at all − the pawn on e5 becomes a target. }
6... O-O
{ As usual, we're trying to launch an attack on the white center asap, meaning we don't waste time on pawn moves unless they're ...d7-d5, or preparing ...d7-d5. }
7. Be3
{ Somewhat shockingly, I believe this is the only way for White to pose any kind of a problem. }
7... c6
{ Shockingly, the inclusion of  7...Re8  8.Bd3  is heavily in White's favor, the difference being  8...c6  9.O-O  d5  10.cxd5  cxd5  11.Bb5!  We're forced to play  11...Rf8  , and are very sad about it. }
8. e5
{ The most principled reaction, in particular because of what the follow-up is.   A@@EndBracket@@  8.Bd3  d5  is a good version of the usual lines.   B@@EndBracket@@  8.Nb3  Re8  is very incongruous play by White.   C@@EndBracket@@  8.c5  Re8  9.f3  b6  is also going to be good for us.  Once the c5-pawn is removed, our ...d5 breaks gain in strength. }
8... Ne8 9. h4
{ This move made me temporarily worried for the health of the whole line. Computers weren't nearly as brave when I recommended this way back in the chess24 series. But we do have a good reply. }
9... Qe7
{ I like this much more than  9...d6  10.e6!  fxe6  11.h5  or the machine's original suggestion of @@StartFEN@@rnbqnrk1/pp1p1pbp/2p3p1/4P3/2PN3P/2N1B3/PP3PP1/R2QKB1R b KQ - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...d5  because White has far fewer ways to sacrifice things for attack here. }
10. h5 d6
{ With the queen on e7, we're quite happy to be allowing e6 since it doesn't break up our K-side. }
11. hxg6 fxg6 12. c5 Bxe5
{ Instead,  12...d5  13.f4  allows White to stabilize in the center. } 13. cxd6
Nxd6 14. Qb3+ Nf7 15. O-O-O Bg7
{ We have a very unclear position on our hands. White definitely has compensation, but we've consolidated, White has no immediate threats, and we're about to start getting the queenside out.  ...a5 with ideas of ...b5/...a4 or ...Qb4 is one way; ...Bg4/...Na6 are also sometimes decent ideas. }
