1. c4
{ The English is easily a topic for a full LTR, but I'll try to show you a way to cut down on the number of options White can choose against us. }
1... g6
{ Just as all those years ago, I'm recommending this somewhat rare move as a reply. In most cases, we will transpose back into classical English setups, but by choosing this move, we're locking White out of some of the lines they could try forcing on us. }
2. e4 e5
{ Another important point − we're not planning to be forced into playing the King's Indian, that should always be a choice you make of your own free will. }
3. d4 { The only way for White to try to punish us. } 3... Nf6
{ The only way to justify allowing White's central push. We can't take on d4 just yet:  3...exd4  4.Qxd4  Nf6  5.Bg5  Be7  6.Nc3  is very bad. }
4. Nf3 exd4 5. e5 Bb4+
{ An update on  5...Ne4  that I was recommending in the chess24 series. This move, almost by force, leads to somewhat Berlin-type endgames, but with Black not really behind in development. }
6. Bd2 Qe7
{ The point − Black's pieces are precariously placed, but there's no way for White to exploit that. }
7. Bxb4
{ 7.Qe2  ,  trying to re-establish the fact that Nf6 is hanging, runs into  7...d3!  8.Qxd3  Nc6!  with an excellent game for Black. }
7... Qxb4+ 8. Qd2 Qxd2+ 9. Nbxd2 Nh5 10. Nxd4 Nc6
{ 10...b6  11.Be2  Bb7  had been tried by Topalov vs. Ding in 2020, but I don't believe it's necessary.  With 10...Nc6, we're pushing vs. the white center since the pawn on e5 is quite vulnerable in many lines. }
11. N2f3 b6 12. Nxc6 dxc6
{ As we know from the Berlin, these endgames can easily turn south for White. }
13. g3 c5 14. Bg2 Bb7 15. O-O Ke7
{ Black was completely fine in Ding-Shankland, chess.com 2019. } *

