1. c4
{ The English is easily a topic for a full LTR, but I'll try to show you a way to cut down on the number of options White can choose against us. }
1... g6
{ Just as all those years ago, I'm recommending this somewhat rare move as a reply. In most cases, we will transpose back into classical English setups, but by choosing this move, we're locking White out of some of the lines they could try forcing on us. }
2. Nc3
{ A@@EndBracket@@  2.d4  Nf6  is, of course, a transposition into our beloved Grünfeld.   B@@EndBracket@@  2.g3  c5  3.Bg2  Bg7  will eventually transpose into the 2.Nc3 c5 lines regardless of which moves come next since  White can’t really do without Nc3.  We use the 2...c5 move order because after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppp1p/6p1/8/2P5/6P1/PP1PPP1P/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Bg7  3.d4  may not allow us to play  symmetrical ...c6 systems @@StartBracket@@Part 1@@EndBracket@@ comfortably. }
2... c5 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 Nc6
{ The starting position of the symmetrical c4/c5 English. White's main option here, by far, is  5.Nf3  , but these days you have to be ready for many other attempts, including some very quirky ones, such as  5.b3  . }
5. a3
{ A logical move − White will often want to push for b4 in these positions. However, it gives us enough time to set up comfortably. }
5... b6
{ Our plan is to play ...Bb7 and then follow it up with either ...Nf6, or perhaps ...d6, ...e6 and ...Nge7, depending on what White does. }
6. b4 Bb7 7. Rb1 d6
{ I believe this to be a bit stronger than  7...Rb8  as it gives us the option to recapture on c5 with the d-pawn. That is relevant in the variation  @@StartFEN@@r2qk1nr/pb2ppbp/1pnp2p1/2p5/1PP5/P1N3P1/3PPPBP/1RBQK1NR w Kkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.bxc5  Bxc3!  9.dxc3  dxc5  with a very big positional advantage. }
8. Bb2
{ White more or less needs to spend a tempo on this since  8.Nf3  allows us an additional option @@StartBracket@@similar to the note on move 7@@EndBracket@@ of  8...Bxc3  9.dxc3  Nf6  , with a very unclear position after, for instance,  10.Bh6  Ng4  11.Qd2  Qc8  ,  intending ...Qe6. }
8... e6 9. Nf3 Nge7 10. O-O
{ It is too early for  10.Nb5  Bxb2  11.Rxb2  Ne5! } 10... cxb4
{ Now we have to be concrete since  10...O-O  11.Nb5!  would be a bit inaccurate. }
11. axb4 Nxb4
{ White gets some temporary initiative for the pawn, but we're easily going to be able to finish development, with a good game. }
12. Ba3 a5 { Returning the pawn is the easiest here. } 13. Bxb4 axb4 14. Rxb4
O-O
{ We have enough play in the center with our bishop pair not to have to worry about the weakness on b6. }
