[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ The dreaded London. I have now spent quite a bit of time trying to figure it out for the course, and I can tell you my intense hatred for it has only increased. }
2... g6
{ We're playing 2...g6 for one major reason. White can start with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/5n2/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  , and as honorable Grünfeld aficionados, we're obliged to reply with  2...g6  , which, after  3.Bf4  , locks us into the fianchetto setups. Therefore, I feel that spending time to learn the other replies to 2.Bf4 is, let's say, an unnecessary investment of time and effort on both mine and your part. }
3. Nc3
{ 3.f3?!  is a very odd move here, and we should welcome it wholeheartedly.  3...d5  4.Nc3  c5  .  The plan of pushing e4 is dead and with it so is any justification for 3.f3. }
3... d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. e3 O-O 6. Be2
{ This variation is much simpler for us than  6.Nb5  , which we'll see later. }
6... c5 7. Ne5 cxd4 8. exd4 Bf5
{ These types of positions are generally quite nice for us. A simple plan of ...Nc6 and ...Rc8, with either ...Nd7 or ...Ne4 to follow later, is enough to deal with White's control of the center, and we have no structural issues to be concerned about at all. }
9. O-O Nc6 10. Nxc6 bxc6
{ A structural change we have no objections to as our center simply gets strengthened. }
11. Na4 Nd7
{ An instructive moment − by preparing ...e7-e5, we want to wake up the sleeping giant on g7. This move also covers the c5-square White was hoping to occupy with the knight, thus keeping it on a4 where it’s not doing very much. }
12. c3 e5 13. Be3 Re8
{ A reasonably well-known position − I would prefer to play as Black since the plan of ...h5-h4, coupled with a solid center and even files for our rooks, gives us the slight upper hand. }
