1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ The dreaded London. I have now spent quite a bit of time trying to figure it out for the course, and I can tell you my intense hatred for it has only increased. }
2... g6
{ We're playing 2...g6 for one major reason. White can start with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/5n2/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  , and as honorable Grünfeld aficionados, we're obliged to reply with  2...g6  , which, after  3.Bf4  , locks us into the fianchetto setups. Therefore, I feel that spending time to learn the other replies to 2.Bf4 is, let's say, an unnecessary investment of time and effort on both mine and your part. }
3. Nc3
{ 3.f3?!  is a very odd move here, and we should welcome it wholeheartedly.  3...d5  4.Nc3  c5  .  The plan of pushing e4 is dead and with it so is any justification for 3.f3. }
3... d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. e3 O-O 6. Nb5
{ The only way White has here, to play for anything significant. } 6... Na6
{ This is the central position of the entire Nc3 group of move orders. White tried a whole bunch of moves here, but in my opinion, the only two that are worth anything are the two moves of Harry the h-pawn. }
7. h3
{ White badly needs to secure this bishop on the h2-b8 diagonal, as you will see time and again in all the other lines. }
7... Ne4
{ A very concrete response − we're fighting for central control, and also preemptively challenging the Nc3 if White chooses to reply to ...c6 by returning the Nb5 there. }
8. Nd2 c6
{ 8...Nd6  as seen  in Rapport-Grischuk, chess.com 2017 is less convincing since White is not obliged to retreat the knight from b5. }
9. Nxe4 dxe4 10. Nc3
{ Our structure has been compromised, but in return, we get to attack the white center. }
10... c5 11. Nxe4 cxd4 12. exd4 Qd5
{ We're more interested in gaining a lot of tempi challenging the white pieces in the center than in winning the pawn back immediately. }
13. Nc3 Qf5 14. Be3 Nb4 15. Rc1 Rd8
{ The edge in development gives us plenty of play for the pawn and the d4-pawn can be won back easily if we want, e.g.  16.Bc4  Bxd4!  17.Bxd4  e5  with comfortable equality. }
