[White "Quickstarter Guide 1.d4 & Others"]
[Black "Torre Attack 3.Bg5 Bg7 4.Nbd2 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bg5
{ This used to be a very popular line − in fact, I played a decent amount of it myself with White, in my Colle-blighted youth. By 2022, it is very clearly a poor relative of the London in terms of volume and general perception, but it remains very playable, of course.  In effect, we'll be playing the Réti Opening a tempo down @@StartBracket@@imagine the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  d5  2.g3  Bg4  3.Bg2  Nf6  lines with reversed colors@@EndBracket@@.   The extra tempo makes White's life quite comfortable in that comparison, of course, but the nature of the positions we will see in this chapter is slow enough for us not to have to worry about tempi all that much.  Conceptually, Black has two major approaches to this line: we can play ...d6 or ...d5, and that will, to a very large extent, define our next plans. I believe the ...d5 systems are fine, but I personally always preferred setups with ...d6, and this is what I will be recommending, in particular with a view to playing ...c5, ...cxd4, and pushing for a reasonably early ...e7-e5.   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppp1p/5np1/8/3P4/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  − this move order more or less forces us to play  3...d5  since we don't really want to play the pure Pirc.  4.Bg5  transposes after  4...Bg7  , but even stronger is  4...Ne4!  grabbing the initiative. }
3... Bg7 4. Nbd2 { By far the most popular move. } 4... c5 5. e3 cxd4
{ I like clarifying the structure as early as possible. It also has the added bonus of removing ideas of Bxf6 and Ne4 from the menu. }
6. exd4 h6
{ I tried a number of other moves here, but I think this is the way to go. We're once again asking White to determine what they want to do with that bishop. Additionally, it's important for us to be able to play ...g6-g5, unpinning the Nf6, if we need it later. }
7. Bxf6
{ Somewhat surprisingly, I believe this is the strongest option for White. }
7... Bxf6 8. Bd3
{ White's gotten rid of what often feels in these lines is the worst piece, and is now planning to play O-O, c3, Re1, and then perhaps try to exploit the softening of our K-side by pushing h4-h5 @@StartBracket@@sometimes White could try this even without castling, but since we can pretty much always meet h4 with ...h5, there is no reason to worry@@EndBracket@@. }
8... d6 9. c3 Nc6
{ 9...O-O  10.h4  h5  is also fine, but not committing to castling yet is more flexible. }
10. O-O O-O 11. d5 Ne5 12. Nxe5 dxe5
{ By recapturing on e5 with the pawn, Black signals the march of the kingside pawns. Next up, we remove the bishop and push ...f7-f5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide 1.d4 & Others"]
[Black "2.Nf3 g6 3.Nbd2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Nbd2
{ This seemingly innocuous move has gained a lot of popularity in recent years. The point is seen in the line  3...d5  @@StartBracket@@Black does normally want to avoid  allowing e2-e4,  although the option of  3...Bg7  4.e4  d6  , switching to a Pirc, does exist.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/5np1/3p4/3P4/5N2/PPPNPPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  Bg7  5.b4!?  ,  where White will be going for a plan of gaining space on the queenside, heavily discouraging the ...c5 counterplay, and planning to go for c4 later on.  We have a lot of possible options in response, and the one I am proposing has the advantage of putting White's plan under immediate pressure. It can also lead to some very wild complications, which I tend to favor whenever possible in the barrens of the Anti-Grünfeld. }
3... c5
{ As a safer backup plan, I would suggest something along the lines of  3...d5  4.e3  a5!?  I really don't like allowing the b4 space-grab.  5.c4  Bg7  6.b3  O-O  7.Bb2  e6!?  8.Be2  b6  9.O-O  Bb7  ,  aiming to finish development with ...Nbd7, ...Qe7, and then start looking for ...c5. }
4. e4
{ A very rare move already, but the only one, I believe, that has any shot of offering White any edge. In practice, White overwhelmingly chooses either  4.dxc5  or  4.e3  .   4.c3  cxd4  5.cxd4  is yet another instance of a very bad runout for White. After  5...d5!  ,  followed by ...Nc6, the difference in the Nd2 and ...Nc6 development makes Black very happy. }
4... cxd4 5. e5 Nd5 6. Bc4
{ This move is almost a novelty, with very very few games in my database − but it's by far the best in the position. }
6... Nb6 7. Bb3
{ Now we have to be extremely careful since White's play against the f7-pawn @@StartBracket@@and the archetypical for the 2020s plans of h4-h5 once we castle@@EndBracket@@ are very dangerous. }
7... Bg7
{ More precise than  7...Nc6  8.Ng5  since being able to castle at will is much more important  than protecting d4 here. }
8. Ne4 { 8.Ng5?  d5  9.exd6  O-O!  is precisely why we played 7...Bg7. } 8...
Nc6 9. Bg5 O-O { We can't allow Nd6+, of course. } 10. h4 h6
{ We don't need to remove the e5-pawn to free up our own play. And if I'm honest, the final position of the line is crazy enough to make me forgive this move for usurping the place of  10...Nxe5  . }
11. h5 { Absolutely the only way to continue. } 11... hxg5 12. hxg6 e6
{ Of course, the Bb3 needs to be neutralized asap. } 13. gxf7+
{ Once again, the only way to continue the attack. In fact, White's next few moves are all but forced. }
13... Rxf7 14. Nd6 { Black can just ignore the threat. } 14... Qe7 15. Nxf7
Qxf7 16. Nxg5 Qg6 { We're ready to assume control. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
