[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide 1.d4 & Others"]
[Black "Colle System 2.Nf3 g6 3.e3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3
{ 2.e3  g6  is going to be roughly the same −  White can’t really play the Colle without Nf3 unless they want to suddenly switch to playing the Stonewall, which doesn’t scare us either. }
2... g6 3. e3
{ You can make an argument that being locked into the fianchetto systems is a bit of a drawback vs. the London. It is, however, an upgrade against the Colle − and I say that as someone who's played a LOT of Colle in my youth. By not even providing White with an easily understood plan of pushing e3-e4 after the opening, we will achieve very comfortable positions by almost any logical means. }
3... Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O c5
{ I like this better than  5...d5  since that allows  6.b4!?  − a theme I mentioned in the3.Nbd2 files, which is one of the better ideas White can lean into after playing the uninspiring 3.e3. }
6. dxc5 Na6
{ I prefer this to  6...Qa5  7.c4  Qxc5  8.Nc3  ,  which is also not bad at all for us, but does offer White some chances for an edge. The knight recapturing that pawn is infinitely better than the queen, meaning White has to take on a6 in order to have any hopes of getting anywhere. }
7. Bxa6 bxa6
{ Our plan is to play ...Bb7, and then win the pawn back with either ...Qc7/...Rc8 or ...Ne4, or perhaps both. }
8. b3 { White needs to solve the issue of developing the Bc1. } 8... Ne4 9. Nd4
Bb7 10. c4
{ And now I quite like taking on c5 with the rook, stopping White from developing the b1-knight to c3 unimpeded. }
10... Rc8 11. Ba3
{ Ba3 can be met by more waiting moves since White doesn't really have a smart follow-up. }
11... Re8
{ I like 11...Re8 the most here, moving the rook away from the x-ray of the Ba3, and protecting e7. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide 1.d4 & Others"]
[Black "Veresov Attack 2.Nc3 d5 3.Bg5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 { Threatening 3.e4, so our reply is semi-forced here. } 2...
d5
{ The big negative effect of playing Nc3 so early, with the pawn back on c2, is that White won't be able to challenge our center with c4 any time soon. And for that very same reason, we're even happier than usual pushing ...c5 ourselves. }
3. Bg5
{ The Veresov Attack proper, so to speak. It's ambitious, but also, happily for us, not very good. White definitely can @@StartBracket@@and should@@EndBracket@@ go back to London-related things with  3.Bf4  . We can respond with  3...g6  − see therelevant chapter, to keep continuity throughout the course, or opt for  3...c5  , which is a safe backupline. }
3... Nbd7
{ A very solid move, combining defense against the spoilation of our kingside pawn structure with preparation for the ...c5 break.   Note that  3...e6?  4.e4  commits the unforgivable sin of suddenly making us play the French. }
4. Qd3
{ This move has been played by some good players, Hikaru among them, but it's not very good. }
4... h6
{ 4...c5  is played much more often and leads to positions that are good for Black, but the text move is more efficient. }
5. Bh4 c5 6. O-O-O c4
{ Castling long is completely unplayable since we can play ...g5 in response to Qg3. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide 1.d4 & Others"]
[Black "Veresov Attack 2.Nc3 d5 3.Bg5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 { Threatening 3.e4, so our reply is semi-forced here. } 2...
d5
{ The big negative effect of playing Nc3 so early, with the pawn back on c2, is that White won't be able to challenge our center with c4 any time soon. And for that very same reason, we're even happier than usual pushing ...c5 ourselves. }
3. Bg5
{ The Veresov Attack proper, so to speak. It's ambitious, but also, happily for us, not very good. White definitely can @@StartBracket@@and should@@EndBracket@@ go back to London-related things with  3.Bf4  . We can respond with  3...g6  − see therelevant chapter, to keep continuity throughout the course, or opt for  3...c5  , which is a safe backupline. }
3... Nbd7
{ A very solid move, combining defense against the spoilation of our kingside pawn structure with preparation for the ...c5 break.   Note that  3...e6?  4.e4  commits the unforgivable sin of suddenly making us play the French. }
4. f3
{ This is not great at all, but it's consistent with the inventor's vision. }
4... h6
{ The immediate  4...c5  is also very good, but there is a specific reason to want to include ...h6 and ...Bh4 first. }
5. Bh4 c5 { And now we pounce. } 6. e4
{ Pretty much the only way to continue. } 6... dxe4 7. fxe4 Qb6
{ This is a winning attempt since we actually have a forced draw.   7...Qa5  creates a lot of pressure vs. the white center and pretty much forces White to play  8.e5!  as everything else is quite bad.  8...cxd4  9.Qxd4  Qxe5  10.Qxe5  Nxe5  11.Bg3  Nc6  12.Nb5  Kd8  13.Nc7  Rb8  14.Nb5  , and we should take the perpetual with  14...Ra8  since  14...e5  15.O-O-O  followed by Nf3 does give White decent play for the pawn. }
8. Nf3 { 8.e5?  cxd4!  is bad. } 8... a6
{ A very useful all-purpose move here, stopping all kinds of future counterplay with Nb5 and Bb5. Specifically, we're now happy to take on b2 if allowed, since we don't have to worry about the Nb5 riposte. }
9. e5
{ 9.Na4  Qa5+  10.c3  g5!  and we're ready to start collecting in the center. }
9... Qxb2 10. Na4 Qa3 11. c3
{ The position looks messy for a second but Black has an efficient antidote. }
11... b5 12. exf6 Qxa4 13. Qxa4 bxa4
{ We have an extra pawn. Yes, it's on a4, but it's still one more pawn White doesn't have. }
*

