[White "Quickstarter Guide 1.d4 & Others"]
[Black "Trompowsky Attack 2.Bg5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5
{ The Trompowsky has been somewhat surpassed in recent years by its more restrained @@StartBracket@@or, shall we say, 'boring'?@@EndBracket@@ brother the London − but it's still an occasional visitor even at the very top level. And here  (an important deviation from my approach to the London for this series)  , I will not commit to playing ...g6 anyway since the Tromp players don't have the option of forcing us to do it by starting with Nf3 first. }
2... d5
{ In my own games, I have always played  2...Ne4  , but that's mainly due to inertia and laziness. The text move is much more sensible. }
3. Nd2 c5 4. dxc5 e6 5. e4 h6
{ There's an absolutely mad line starting with  5...Bxc5  6.e5  Qb6  which would be fun to suggest since I believe it works, but the text move is a more sensible solution. }
6. Bh4 Be7
{ There's nothing wrong with the simple  6...dxe4  7.Nxe4  Qa5+  8.Nd2  Qxc5  ,  as was played by Aronian vs. Karjakin in 2020 − but this is sharper and more ambitious, I believe. We're maintaining the pressure in the center while finishing development, and letting White decide what to do with the hanging e4 and c5-pawns. }
7. Ngf3 dxe4 8. Bxf6 Bxf6 9. Nxe4 Qxd1+
{ Obviously, being able to take on b2 next, this is an endgame we are not fearing. }
10. Rxd1 Bxb2 11. Bb5+ Ke7
{ Black is doing fine with the flawless pawn structure and the bishop pair. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide 1.d4 & Others"]
[Black "Trompowsky Attack 2.Bg5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5
{ The Trompowsky has been somewhat surpassed in recent years by its more restrained @@StartBracket@@or, shall we say, 'boring'?@@EndBracket@@ brother the London − but it's still an occasional visitor even at the very top level. And here  (an important deviation from my approach to the London for this series)  , I will not commit to playing ...g6 anyway since the Tromp players don't have the option of forcing us to do it by starting with Nf3 first. }
2... d5
{ In my own games, I have always played  2...Ne4  , but that's mainly due to inertia and laziness. The text move is much more sensible. }
3. Bxf6 gxf6
{ 3...exf6  is safer  and entirely playable too. We'll be developing the bishop to d6, castle K-side, and when White plays c4, we'll trade and aim to finish development by playing ...f5 and ...Nd7-f6.    3...gxf6  is more concrete.  We're playing ...c5 next move, almost no matter what, and then aiming to go for very fast development in the center with ...Nc6 and ...e5. The doubling of the f-pawns is somewhat annoying, but it also gives us additional firepower by further supporting that ...e5 push. }
4. e3 c5 5. c4
{ A new-fangled way of playing this position, which gained a lot of popularity in recent years. }
5... cxd4 6. exd4 { The only way to continue the fight here. } 6... Nc6 7. Nc3
{ 7.Nf3  e5  transposes to the4.Nf3 variation. } 7... e5
{ Much better than  7...dxc4  8.d5  Ne5  9.Bxc4  which is quite unclear,  despite the machine really hating it for White. }
8. cxd5 Nxd4 9. Nf3
{ In the 4 games that have so far reached this position, everybody played the text move, which more or less loses. }
9... Qb6 10. Rb1 Rg8
{ White is in severe trouble since it will be very difficult to complete development. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
