[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide 1.d4 & Others"]
[Black "1.g3 d5 2.Bg2"]
[Result "*"]

1. g3 d5
{ The most consistent way of playing against 1.g3. We're immediately beginning the fight for the center.  1...e5  would also be quite logical if not for the fact that  2.c4  , pivoting into the English, exists. }
2. Bg2 e5
{ Now that White can't force us to play the English, we're quite happy to play ...e5. }
3. c4 d4 4. d3 a5
{ We're making this move early so that we won't forget to make it later.  4...Nc6  is also playable, and should lead to the same, just remember to play ...a5 in time.  5.Nf3  Nf6  6.O-O  a5!  Just not  6...Be7?  7.b4  , which was suddenly very good for White in Morozevich-Karjakin, 2012. The problem is that  7...Bxb4  now runs into  8.Nxe5!  Nxe5  9.Qa4+  winning back the piece with the better game. }
5. Nf3 Nc6 6. O-O Nf6
{ This is a very nice Réti for us since White is too slow. } 7. Na3 Bc5 8. Nb5
{ An empty gesture. } 8... O-O 9. Bg5 Be7 10. e3 h6
{ We were following Topalov-Giri, Leuven 2016, but here, instead of  10...dxe3  , Black should have played the text move. }
11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. exd4 exd4
{ Eventually, we'll move our Nc6 somewhere, push the Nb5 back with ...c6, and stand very well. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide 1.d4 & Others"]
[Black "Symmetrical Line 1.g3 d5 2.Nf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. g3 d5
{ The most consistent way of playing against 1.g3. We're immediately beginning the fight for the center.  1...e5  would also be quite logical if not for the fact that  2.c4  , pivoting into the English, exists. }
2. Nf3
{ A more sensible option, once again feeding into either the g3 Grünfeld or the Tabiya. A few rare lines which lead to neither are covered here. }
2... g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. d4 { 4.d3  Nf6  5.O-O  O-O  iscovered elsewhere. } 4...
Nf6 5. O-O O-O
{ The Tabiya − this position can arise by a multitude of move orders, and while we're not worried about White not playing  6.c4  transposing back intoPart 1, it is of course important to have a road map for the @@StartBracket@@many, sooo many@@EndBracket@@ little moves White could try here. }
6. c3
{ Probably the main line of the non-main lines by now, pioneered @@StartBracket@@or, rather, re-imagined@@EndBracket@@ by Vladimir Kramnik in the 2010s. }
6... a5 { I like this move the most, yet again. } 7. Bf4 a4
{ Continuing to gain space. } 8. Nbd2 Nbd7 9. Rc1 c6
{ Calmly finishing development and waiting for White to show their hand. We're planning to play ...h6, hinting at g5 and chasing down the Bf4 while ...Nb6 is also an idea. }
10. c4 h6 11. h3
{ Stopping Ng4 so that the bishop can retreat to e3 safely in case of ...g5. }
11... Nb6 12. b3 axb3 13. axb3 Be6 { We're extremely solid. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide 1.d4 & Others"]
[Black "Larsen 1.b3"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3 e5 { Let's play in the center and show them how it's done. } 2. Bb2 Nc6
3. c4
{ I assume by this point most of the 1.b3 games you're likely to encounter will be against the hard-core #Cowboys, so we're making the 3.c4 lines central here. In the past,  3.e3  was much more prevalent, though. }
3... Nge7
{ I think this is a little bit more flexible than  3...Nf6  , but in most cases, it will all come to the same. }
4. e3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. a3
{ This is what the #cowboys are doing @@StartBracket@@I think?@@EndBracket@@. There's a wide choice of very good ideas but I like the setup Alexander Grischuk showed. }
6... Be6 7. Nf3 f6 8. Qc2 Qd7
{ We want to castle Q-side and then start on the ...g5-g4 plans. } 9. b4
{ White needs to be quick and this move creates the idea of b5 and d4. } 9...
O-O-O
{ I like this simple move best, but you can also play the alternative  9...Bf5  . }
10. Nc3 { Too slow. } 10... Nxc3 11. Bxc3 Kb8
{ Not committing to ...g5 yet makes it easier to deal with d2-d4 later.  11...g5  12.b5   12.h3?!  Kb8  13.Be2  Rg8  was very good for Black in Ivanisevic-Grischuk, chess.com 2021.  12...Ne7  13.d4  g4  14.Nd2  is quite unclear. Note that @@StartFEN@@2kr1b1r/pppqn2p/4bp2/1P2p1p1/3P4/P1B1PN2/2Q2PPP/R3KB1R b KQ - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...e4?  14.Nxg5!  fxg5  15.d5  is wrong, and  illustrates why keeping that pawn on g7 for a while yet might be stronger. }
12. d4 e4 13. Nd2 f5 14. Be2 Bd6 { Black is doing quite well. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide 1.d4 & Others"]
[Black "Bird 1.f4"]
[Result "*"]

1. f4
{ The fabled reversed Dutch. Turns out even a tempo-up Dutch is still not great, who could have known. }
1... d5 2. Nf3 c5 3. g3
{ Most people play the Bird with the intention of playing the tempo up Leningrad, we'll take a brief look at the other options in thededicated chapter, too. }
3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O Nc6 6. d3
{ 6.c3  doesn't have any independent value:  6...Nf6  7.d3  O-O  and we transpose back to the current variation. }
6... Nf6 7. c3 O-O 8. Qc2 d4 9. Na3
{ 9.e4?  dxe3  10.Bxe3  Bf5-+  is just a disaster. White can still protect d3, but ...c5-c4 is a major threat as well. }
9... Nd5 { The position is comfortably better for us. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Reti 1.Nf3 Nf6 − 2nd move Sidelines"]
[Black "1.Nf3 and 2.d3 − 4.g3 Setup"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6
{ In this little chapter and the next one, we will deal with all the lines where White opens with 1.Nf3 and then declines to follow up with 2.c4 in reply to 1...Nf6. }
2. d3
{ If White wants to play the King's Indian Attack, there are ways to telegraph it less. By opening with  2.d3  , White gives us such ample warning regarding the future plans that we can choose exactly how to set up in response. Beginning with  2.g3  is more subtle. }
2... d5 3. Nbd2 Nc6
{ There's nothing wrong withproceeding as we would do vs. 2.g3, and playing  3...g6  ,  followed by ...Bg7, but since White's intentions are clear, we can do better. }
4. g3 e5 5. Bg2 Bc5 6. O-O O-O 7. e4 Re8 8. c3 a5
{ We have a very comfortable reversed-Pirc type of position here. We're intending to play ...h6, ...Be6, the Bc5 can retreat to f8 later, which provides additional security for our kingside − but more importantly, White does not really have an abundance of active plans. We're clearly completely fine. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Reti 1.Nf3 Nf6 − 2nd move Sidelines"]
[Black "1.Nf3 and 2.d3 − 4.e4 Setup"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6
{ In this little chapter and the next one, we will deal with all the lines where White opens with 1.Nf3 and then declines to follow up with 2.c4 in reply to 1...Nf6. }
2. d3
{ If White wants to play the King's Indian Attack, there are ways to telegraph it less. By opening with  2.d3  , White gives us such ample warning regarding the future plans that we can choose exactly how to set up in response. Beginning with  2.g3  is more subtle. }
2... d5 3. Nbd2 Nc6
{ There's nothing wrong withproceeding as we would do vs. 2.g3, and playing  3...g6  ,  followed by ...Bg7, but since White's intentions are clear, we can do better. }
4. e4 e5 5. Be2
{ Via a slightly different move order we've arrived at a position that Baadur Jobava used to play quite a bit with White − and I should know, I lost to him from here. It had little to do with the opening results, though, and much with how brilliant he is when given half a chance. Black is, of course, completely fine after almost any kind of sensible development. }
5... Bc5
{ The natural ...g6 and ...Bg7 wouldn't have been a mistake, or ....Bd6, or ...Be7 − but why not develop this bishop to a good square straight away? }
6. O-O O-O 7. c3 a5
{ As usual, it's quite good for us to prevent the expansion on the Q-side with b4. }
8. a4 Re8
{ The things I said about the very similar position we've seen in the previous variation with the white bishop on g2 are still true here. Our play is quite straightforward: I would start with ...h6 and ...Be6 in almost all eventualities, and then consider ...Qd7 and ...Rad8, or perhaps more space gain with ...d5-d4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Reti 1.Nf3 Nf6 − 2nd move Sidelines"]
[Black "1.Nf3 Nf6 2.b4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6
{ In this little chapter and the next one, we will deal with all the lines where White opens with 1.Nf3 and then declines to follow up with 2.c4 in reply to 1...Nf6. }
2. b4
{ A move we will not encounter very often in our practice. White takes some space on the queenside but, at the same time, overextends. The b4-pawn can easily become vulnerable or a downright target. }
2... g6 3. Bb2 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d5
{ 5...d6  is playable, but I want to mention an interesting idea. } 6. O-O Qd6
{ It's actually quite awkward for White to defend the b4-pawn without making concessions. }
7. a3 a5 8. b5 a4
{ We've isolated White's b5-pawn, turning it into an object of attack. } *

