[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6
{ In this little chapter and the next one, we will deal with all the lines where White opens with 1.Nf3 and then declines to follow up with 2.c4 in reply to 1...Nf6. }
2. b4
{ A move we will not encounter very often in our practice. White takes some space on the queenside but, at the same time, overextends. The b4-pawn can easily become vulnerable or a downright target. }
2... g6 3. Bb2 Bg7 4. e3
{ 4.c4  O-O  transposes  into the 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 g6 −3rd move Sidelines chapter. }
4... O-O 5. Be2 d6 6. d4
{ A@@EndBracket@@  6.O-O  will probably  end up in the 1.Nf3 2.c4 3.b4 territory too  , just a bit later:  6...e5  7.d3  a5!?  8.b5  a4  and now White will find it hard not to play  9.c4  , whichtransposes after  9...Nbd7  .   B@@EndBracket@@  6.c4  e5  and we're once  again back inthe same chapter. }
6... c5
{ This position got a brief mention in theColle chapter, but we could expand it a little bit. }
7. a3 cxd4 8. Nxd4
{ 8.exd4?!  d5  is an obvious illustration of what to avoid if you choose to play b4 early. Now White's structure is permanently compromised. }
8... a5 9. c4 axb4 10. axb4 Rxa1 11. Bxa1 Qb6
{ We have clear play against White's center and Q-side. } *

