{ In this little chapter and the next one, we will deal with all the lines where White opens with 1.Nf3 and then declines to follow up with 2.c4 in reply to 1...Nf6. }
2. b3
{ This move is normally played in order to switch to double fianchetto, and our reply is the same as what I'm recommending in the2.c4 g6 3.b3 lines − let's go full symmetry. }
2... g6 3. Bb2 Bg7 4. g3 b6
{ We can do this later, of course, but developing the bishop to b7 at the same time as White gets theirs to g2 discourages even the mildest shenanigans. }
5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O O-O { White will find it very hard to avoid playing 7.c4. }
7. d4
{ This is an attempt to avoid total symmetry which somewhat surprisingly saw quite a bit of top-level practice in recent years, but Black is fine. }
7... c5
{ We do need to challenge White's center before both d4 and c4 can be played, which would allow meeting ...c5 with d5. }
8. dxc5 bxc5 9. c4 d6 10. Qc2
{ I prefer a slightly different setup to what a number of good players opted for in this position. }
10... e6
{ 10...Nbd7  11.Nc3  Rb8  @@StartBracket@@preparing 12...Ne4  which would currently be bad because of 12.Ng5! using the fact that Bb7 is loose.  @@EndBracket@@, as played,  among others, by So, Duda and Tomashevsky, feels less safe to me. White should stop ...Ne4 by protecting the Bb2.  12.Rab1!   12.Rad1  Ne4  was fine for Black in Nakamura-Duda, St. Petersburg 2018. Black would very much like to trade off some light pieces here.  12...a6  13.Rfd1  Qc7  14.Rd2  , and in another game between the same players: Nakamura-Duda, St. Petersburg 2018 White was ahead. }
11. Nc3 Qe7 12. Rad1 Nc6 13. e3 Rfd8
{ Our knight on c6 is more efficient than its counterpart on c3. We can look to play ...Rac8 and then consider pushing for ...d6-d5. }
