1. Nf3 Nf6
{ In this chapter @@StartBracket@@and the previous one@@EndBracket@@, we will deal with all the lines where White opens with 1.Nf3 and then declines to follow up with 2.c4 in reply to 1...Nf6. }
2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O
{ In the Nf3/g3 systems, and our symmetrical response to them, these moves get made anyway, in some order, so it’s easiest to just get this out of the way. }
5. d3
{ A@@EndBracket@@  5.d4  d5  either leads to Part 1 of the Grünfeld after  6.c4  or to the 1.g3Symmetrical Line after any other 6th move.   B@@EndBracket@@  5.c4  c5  6.Nc3  d5  is covered in the
Symmetrical Grünfeld, leaving only the 5th moves in this chapter. }
5... d5 6. c4 Nc6
{ This somewhat unorthodox reaction is justified as the next moves will show. It prepares play in the center. White is unable to prevent us from establishing a Maroczy-type setup with ...e7-e5. }
7. cxd5 { What else? } 7... Nxd5
{ And now the machine wants to play a very 2020s kind of move, which is a novelty in my database. }
8. h4
{ Against any kind of a normal move, we want to play ...e5, ...Re8 with a very good natural setup, but we can also wait to do that for a while, with useful moves like ...a5 in particular. Since White would clearly like to play Nc3 here, until our pawn lands on e5 this is a legit pawn sacrifice. In view of all that, White is also looking for a good 'pass', and 8.h4 tops that list. }
8... a5
{ Continuing the waiting dance.  8...e5  9.Nc3  is playable for White. } 9. h5
{ Can, and should, be met with the cold-blooded: } 9... gxh5
{ With ...Bg4 to support it, this extra pawn is not worthless at all. } 10. Nc3
Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bxc3 12. Bh6 Re8 13. Rc1 Bf6
{ With an unclear position which I believe favours Black a bit. } *

