[White "2. Fianchetto Variation 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.g3"]
[Black "Fianchetto Variation 2.g3 − 5.d3 d5 6.Nbd2 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6
{ In this chapter @@StartBracket@@and the previous one@@EndBracket@@, we will deal with all the lines where White opens with 1.Nf3 and then declines to follow up with 2.c4 in reply to 1...Nf6. }
2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O
{ In the Nf3/g3 systems, and our symmetrical response to them, these moves get made anyway, in some order, so it’s easiest to just get this out of the way. }
5. d3
{ A@@EndBracket@@  5.d4  d5  either leads to Part 1 of the Grünfeld after  6.c4  or to the 1.g3Symmetrical Line after any other 6th move.   B@@EndBracket@@  5.c4  c5  6.Nc3  d5  is covered in the
Symmetrical Grünfeld, leaving only the 5th moves in this chapter. }
5... d5 6. Nbd2
{ Black has a number of good options here, but we're opting for the simplest one: }
6... c5 7. e4 Nc6
{ We will be playing ...e5 next, and then ...Re8 and ...h6 in most cases, to secure ourselves against potential jumps to g5. Our complete control in the center provides us with very simple play. White is probably not worse yet, the position is quite solid, and playing a Classical King's Indian with an extra tempo can't be too bad − but we're also not going to have any problems either. }
8. c3 e5 9. Re1 h6 10. exd5
{ There's rarely anything better to do for White in this structure. } 10...
Nxd5 11. Nc4 Re8 12. a4 Bf5
{ A very nice position for Black where we are fully mobilized. } *

