[Black "Fianchetto Variation 2.g3 − 5.d3 d5 6.Nbd2 #13 | Alternative 11...a5 *3"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6
{ In this chapter @@StartBracket@@and the previous one@@EndBracket@@, we will deal with all the lines where White opens with 1.Nf3 and then declines to follow up with 2.c4 in reply to 1...Nf6. }
2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O
{ In the Nf3/g3 systems, and our symmetrical response to them, these moves get made anyway, in some order, so it’s easiest to just get this out of the way. }
5. d3
{ A@@EndBracket@@  5.d4  d5  either leads to Part 1 of the Grünfeld after  6.c4  or to the 1.g3Symmetrical Line after any other 6th move.   B@@EndBracket@@  5.c4  c5  6.Nc3  d5  is covered in the
Symmetrical Grünfeld, leaving only the 5th moves in this chapter. }
5... d5 6. Nbd2
{ Black has a number of good options here, but we're opting for the simplest one: }
6... c5 7. e4 Nc6
{ We will be playing ...e5 next, and then ...Re8 and ...h6 in most cases, to secure ourselves against potential jumps to g5. Our complete control in the center provides us with very simple play. White is probably not worse yet, the position is quite solid, and playing a Classical King's Indian with an extra tempo can't be too bad − but we're also not going to have any problems either. }
8. c3 e5 9. Re1 h6 10. exd5
{ There's rarely anything better to do for White in this structure. } 10...
Nxd5 11. Qb3
{ If you don't want to allow an immediate draw, there is a number of playable options here, e.g. }
11... a5
{ Gaining space on the Q-side is always a useful idea as is challenging the Qb3 with ...a5-a4. }
12. a4 b6
{ Making sure we don’t have to worry about the pawn on c5 hanging anymore. }
13. Nxe5
{ Almost forced since  13.Nc4  is very nice for Black as we saw previously. }
13... Nxe5 14. Qxd5 Ra7
{ Trying to bait White into 15.Rxe5.   In fairness, resisting the temptation by playing  15.Qxd8  Rxd8  16.Nc4  Nxd3  17.Rd1  Ba6  18.b3  doesn't put White in any real danger. }
15. Rxe5 Rd7 { A forced sequence follows: } 16. Qe4
{ Anything else would just give up the whole rook on e5. } 16... Bb7 17. Qe2
{ White could choose a different square after ...Bb7, but that wouldn’t change the end result since there’s always the recapture on e5 anyway. }
17... Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Bxe5 19. Qxe5 Re8 20. Qf4 Rxd3 21. Ne4 Re6
{ It turns out that White, despite having two pieces for the rook, has to be quite careful in the face of our complete control over the central files. In fact, the engines suggest everything that is not  22.g4  or  22.h4  straight up loses here. }
*

