2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O
{ In the Nf3/g3 systems, and our symmetrical response to them, these moves get made anyway, in some order, so it’s easiest to just get this out of the way. }
5. d3
{ A@@EndBracket@@  5.d4  d5  either leads to Part 1 of the Grünfeld after  6.c4  or to the 1.g3Symmetrical Line after any other 6th move.   B@@EndBracket@@  5.c4  c5  6.Nc3  d5  is covered in the
Symmetrical Grünfeld, leaving only the 5th moves in this chapter. }
5... d5 6. Nbd2
{ Black has a number of good options here, but we're opting for the simplest one: }
6... c5 7. e4 Nc6
{ We will be playing ...e5 next, and then ...Re8 and ...h6 in most cases, to secure ourselves against potential jumps to g5. Our complete control in the center provides us with very simple play. White is probably not worse yet, the position is quite solid, and playing a Classical King's Indian with an extra tempo can't be too bad − but we're also not going to have any problems either. }
8. Re1 e5 9. exd5 { 9.c3  h6  transposes to the8.c3 variation. } 9... Nxd5 10.
Nc4 f6
{ 10...Re8  allows  11.Ng5!?  and while after the best  11...f5  12.f4  h6  13.Nh3  and now  13...Be6  or  13...Kh7  , Black isn't doing too shabbily, there is no need to allow any of this. }
11. a4 Be6 12. c3 Qd7
{ Once again, we have a very good solid setup, which you can improve by putting the rooks in the center, perhaps tucking the king in with ...Kh8 and ...Bg8, and then considering some kind of play in the center starting with ...f5.   White, in the meantime, will struggle to generate any kind of active plans, since the Nd2-e4 plan can be met by ...b6, and then White is once again somewhat stuck. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Reti 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 g6 − 3rd move Sidelines"]
[Black "1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.b3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
{ This is a very serious move, of course. In many cases White will have the option of transposing into the Grünfeld later on if we decide to play ...Nf6 and ...g6 here, as we will. But in this volume we'll be dealing with the options White can choose that don't allow us to play our beloved opening. }
1... Nf6 2. c4
{ 2.d4  g6  transposes to various other lines, depending on White's next move. }
2... g6 3. b3
{ Definitely has a point − White will want to play the double fianchetto, while also somewhat discouraging us from the ...c6/...d5 setups by postponing d4. However, there is no reason for us not to accept the invitation to play the fully symmetrical double fianchetto positions. }
3... Bg7 4. Bb2 O-O 5. d4 { Way too optimistic. } 5... c5
{ White will have to accept immediate equality. } 6. d5 e6
{ This is not a very good version of the Benoni structures since White rarely wants to spend two tempi to develop the bishop to b2 instead of developing the K-side. }
*

