{ Of course, we're not interested in allowing a weakness on c5 after  9...bxc5?!  10.cxd5  . After the text move, we're often ready to sacrifice the pawn  on c4 for development and very typical play against the broken-up white Q-side you often see in Grünfeld and even some Nimzo, e.g. }
10. cxb6 axb6 11. bxc4 Qc7
{ We're completely fine due to our consistent pressure on the Q-side which doesn't even require immediate threats. White will be tied down to the protection of the a2 and c4-pawns forever. }
12. Qb3 Nbd7 { The knight is almost always very well placed on c5. } 13. Nbd2
e5 { Starting active play in the center. } 14. Nxe5
{ White will pay a high price for grabbing the pawn. } 14... Bxg2 15. Nxd7 Qxd7
{ Black wins material. } *

