[White "3. Reti 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 g6 − 3rd move Sidelines"]
[Black "1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.g3"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
{ This is a very serious move, of course. In many cases White will have the option of transposing into the Grünfeld later on if we decide to play ...Nf6 and ...g6 here, as we will. But in this volume we'll be dealing with the options White can choose that don't allow us to play our beloved opening. }
1... Nf6 2. c4
{ 2.d4  g6  transposes to various other lines, depending on White's next move. }
2... g6 3. g3
{ A solid option − my suggestion is to wait until White castles before committing to a structure in the center, for reasons that should be intuitively obvious to anyone who's had to deal with A0, Leela and their ilk. There's really no reason at all to give White any h2-h4 connected options if we don't have to :@@EndBracket@@ }
3... Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O
{ We have the option of playing  4...c6  to try to get back to the symmetrical 3.g3 Grünfeld, but I'm giving something else for two reasons.   1. White can postpone the d4 move and play b3/Bb2 first, not really allowing us the exact same positions.  2. The existence of the 3.Nc3 Bg7 4.g3 move order means we can't ALWAYS rely on ...c6/...d5, and therefore it makes sense to give uniform recommendations here so that's easier to remember what we're aiming for. }
5. Nc3 { 5.d4  c6  will transpose into the3.g3 Grünfeld. } 5... c5
{ Transposes to the next chapters after both  6.d4  and  6.O-O  . We're not rushing with @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppppppbp/5np1/8/2P5/2N2NP1/PP1PPPBP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 4 5@@EndFEN@@  5...d5  because there's absolutely no point allowing  6.cxd5  Nxd5  7.h4! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Symmetrical Grünfeld 3.Nc3 Bg7 4.g3 − 6.O-O"]
[Black "Symmetrical Grünfeld 6.O-O − 8.Qb3"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
{ This is a very serious move, of course. In many cases White will have the option of transposing into the Grünfeld later on if we decide to play ...Nf6 and ...g6 here, as we will. But in this volume we'll be dealing with the options White can choose that don't allow us to play our beloved opening. }
1... Nf6 2. c4
{ 2.d4  g6  transposes to various other lines, depending on White's next move. }
2... g6 3. Nc3 Bg7
{ 3...d5  has been my move of choice for many years, but I'm not quite happy enough with  4.cxd5  Nxd5  , and now, to the surprise of absolutely nobody in the 2020s,  5.h4!? }
4. g3
{ There are a lot of transpositions when we're discussing the Nf3/c4/g3 lines, and I'm making this move order the main one because it's the only one that really properly discourages Black from going back to the ...c6/...d5 systems in reply − and because this move order exists, I will not be recommending ...c6/...d5 anywhere else, either.   The point is that with the knight already on c3,  4...c6  can and should be met by  5.e4  , and we're not going to get back to the symmetrical Grünfeld positions we've discussed in Part 1 of this LTR. }
4... O-O 5. Bg2 c5
{ We avoid the Grünfeld-type move  5...d5  , as  6.cxd5  Nxd5  7.h4!  is, once again, bothering. }
6. O-O d5
{ Now that White no longer has any of those scary h4 ideas, we're ready to commit to ...d5. }
7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Qb3
{ Not very critical and it allows us a very nice Maroczy setup. } 8... Nc7 9.
Qc4 { Or  9.d3  Nc6  10.Be3  b6  which is similar to the main line. } 9... Ne6
10. d3 Nc6
{ And we're already quite happy with things. Our plan is to play ...b6, either immediately or after preparing it with ...Rb8 or ...Bd7, and then use the d4-square as a very nice base of operations. Playing e3 to stop that results in White acquiring a weakness on d3, which we also don’t mind at all. }
*

