[Black "Symmetrical Grünfeld 6.O-O − 8.Qa4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
{ This is a very serious move, of course. In many cases White will have the option of transposing into the Grünfeld later on if we decide to play ...Nf6 and ...g6 here, as we will. But in this volume we'll be dealing with the options White can choose that don't allow us to play our beloved opening. }
1... Nf6 2. c4
{ 2.d4  g6  transposes to various other lines, depending on White's next move. }
2... g6 3. Nc3 Bg7
{ 3...d5  has been my move of choice for many years, but I'm not quite happy enough with  4.cxd5  Nxd5  , and now, to the surprise of absolutely nobody in the 2020s,  5.h4!? }
4. g3
{ There are a lot of transpositions when we're discussing the Nf3/c4/g3 lines, and I'm making this move order the main one because it's the only one that really properly discourages Black from going back to the ...c6/...d5 systems in reply − and because this move order exists, I will not be recommending ...c6/...d5 anywhere else, either.   The point is that with the knight already on c3,  4...c6  can and should be met by  5.e4  , and we're not going to get back to the symmetrical Grünfeld positions we've discussed in Part 1 of this LTR. }
4... O-O 5. Bg2 c5
{ We avoid the Grünfeld-type move  5...d5  , as  6.cxd5  Nxd5  7.h4!  is, once again, bothering. }
6. O-O d5
{ Now that White no longer has any of those scary h4 ideas, we're ready to commit to ...d5. }
7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Qa4
{ My old recommendation still stands − in fact, I was quite chuffed to see Vishy play the exact line I believe I was the first one to point out against Navara in 2018. }
8... Nc6 9. Qc4 { This is the only point of Qa4. } 9... Nxc3 10. dxc3 Qb6 11.
Ng5 h6 12. Ne4 Be6
{ This very nice sequence shows that the ‘pressure’ against the c5-pawn is ephemeral. }
13. Qxc5 f5
{ Forcing White to take on b6, thus including our Ra8 in the game. } 14. Qxb6
axb6 15. Nd2 Rxa2
{ Black equalized easily in Navara-Anand, Batumi 2018, just as I suggested in my course! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Symmetrical Grünfeld 3.Nc3 Bg7 4.g3 − 6.O-O"]
[Black "Symmetrical Grünfeld 6.O-O − 8.Qa4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
{ This is a very serious move, of course. In many cases White will have the option of transposing into the Grünfeld later on if we decide to play ...Nf6 and ...g6 here, as we will. But in this volume we'll be dealing with the options White can choose that don't allow us to play our beloved opening. }
1... Nf6 2. c4
{ 2.d4  g6  transposes to various other lines, depending on White's next move. }
2... g6 3. Nc3 Bg7
{ 3...d5  has been my move of choice for many years, but I'm not quite happy enough with  4.cxd5  Nxd5  , and now, to the surprise of absolutely nobody in the 2020s,  5.h4!? }
4. g3
{ There are a lot of transpositions when we're discussing the Nf3/c4/g3 lines, and I'm making this move order the main one because it's the only one that really properly discourages Black from going back to the ...c6/...d5 systems in reply − and because this move order exists, I will not be recommending ...c6/...d5 anywhere else, either.   The point is that with the knight already on c3,  4...c6  can and should be met by  5.e4  , and we're not going to get back to the symmetrical Grünfeld positions we've discussed in Part 1 of this LTR. }
4... O-O 5. Bg2 c5
{ We avoid the Grünfeld-type move  5...d5  , as  6.cxd5  Nxd5  7.h4!  is, once again, bothering. }
6. O-O d5
{ Now that White no longer has any of those scary h4 ideas, we're ready to commit to ...d5. }
7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Qa4
{ My old recommendation still stands − in fact, I was quite chuffed to see Vishy play the exact line I believe I was the first one to point out against Navara in 2018. }
8... Nc6 9. Qc4 { This is the only point of Qa4. } 9... Nxc3 10. dxc3 Qb6 11.
Qh4 Rd8
{ Taking control over the only open file makes a lot of sense, but the positions arising after 12.Ng5 are quite non-standard, as you will see. Another option is  11...Bd7  12.Ng5  h6  13.Nf3  g5  14.Qe4  Rad8  15.h4  g4  as in Almasi-Kulaots BL 2019, where Black was fine. }
12. Re1 Bd7
{ Our plan of playing ...Be8, and then perhaps doubling on the d-file, might seem slow − but White really isn't doing much either, due to how annoying our pressure against the b2-pawn is.   Note that  13.Rb1  Bxc3?  simply loses after  14.Ng5!  h5  15.Qc4  with a classic double attack. Black can play @@StartFEN@@r2r2k1/pp1bppbp/1qn3p1/2p5/7Q/2P2NP1/PP2PPBP/1RB1R1K1 b - - 6 13@@EndFEN@@  13...h5!?  though, preparing the capture on c3 and preventing Bh6. }
