1. Nf3
{ This is a very serious move, of course. In many cases White will have the option of transposing into the Grünfeld later on if we decide to play ...Nf6 and ...g6 here, as we will. But in this volume we'll be dealing with the options White can choose that don't allow us to play our beloved opening. }
1... Nf6 2. c4
{ 2.d4  g6  transposes to various other lines, depending on White's next move. }
2... g6 3. Nc3 Bg7
{ 3...d5  has been my move of choice for many years, but I'm not quite happy enough with  4.cxd5  Nxd5  , and now, to the surprise of absolutely nobody in the 2020s,  5.h4!? }
4. g3
{ There are a lot of transpositions when we're discussing the Nf3/c4/g3 lines, and I'm making this move order the main one because it's the only one that really properly discourages Black from going back to the ...c6/...d5 systems in reply − and because this move order exists, I will not be recommending ...c6/...d5 anywhere else, either.   The point is that with the knight already on c3,  4...c6  can and should be met by  5.e4  , and we're not going to get back to the symmetrical Grünfeld positions we've discussed in Part 1 of this LTR. }
4... O-O 5. Bg2 c5
{ We avoid the Grünfeld-type move  5...d5  , as  6.cxd5  Nxd5  7.h4!  is, once again, bothering. }
6. O-O d5
{ Now that White no longer has any of those scary h4 ideas, we're ready to commit to ...d5. }
7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Nxd5 Qxd5 9. d3
{ This is the old main line and it's by now well established what we should do against it. }
9... Nc6 10. Be3
{ White needs to be fast since structurally we're doing more than fine. } 10...
Bxb2 11. Rb1 Bf6 { Having the e7-pawn protected will help in a few lines. } 12.
Qa4 Qd7 { A very nice tactical way to solve all of our issues. } 13. Bxc5 b6
14. Be3 Nd4 { The point of placing our queen on d7, of course. } 15. Qxd7 Nxe2+
16. Kh1 Bxd7 { This is very bad for White. } *

