7. dxc5 Qa5 8. cxd5 { This is easy to deal with. } 8... Nxd5 9. Qxd5 Bxc3+ 10.
Bd2 Rd8 { White faces a choice between  11.Bxc3  or  11.Qxd8+  . } 11. Bxc3
{ Now a very forced sequence begins: } 11... Qxc3+ 12. bxc3 Rxd5 13. Rd1
{ The only move to cause any trouble − if we get to recapture on c5 unimpeded, we have every reason to be optimistic about the future with our better structure and the weakness on c3. }
13... Rxc5 14. Rd8+ Kg7 15. Nd4 { Trying to stop ...Nc6. } 15... Nd7 16. Kd2
Nb6
{ By protecting the Ra8, we are intending to develop our Bc8 and trade off the intruder on d8. We will successfully unpin ourselves, eventually. }
17. Rb1 Nc4+ 18. Ke1 a6
{ Another clever idea − the fact that the rook on d8 is unprotected means we don’t have to protect the b7-pawn, giving us time to prepare ...Ra7. Our better pawn structure ensures our safety. }
