2... g6
{ In this chapter, we will finally get to the absolute main line of the Nf3/c4 complex: 3.Nc3 Bg7 4.e4. }
3. Nc3 Bg7
{ 3...d5  has been my move of choice for many years, but I'm not quite happy enough with  4.cxd5  Nxd5  , and now, to the surprise of absolutely nobody in the 2020s,  5.h4!? }
4. e4 { 4.d4  d5  − transposes to a properGrünfeld as seen in Part  1. } 4...
e5
{ I wasn't going to abandon you to the KID, of course. Having said that, in the KID we wouldn't be a pawn down by move five. }
5. Nxe5
{ The only move worth the name here, but I will note that  5.d4  exd4  6.Nxd4  O-O  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.c4  g6  2.e4  e5  3.Nf3  Bg7  , which is covered in theEnglish chapter with 3.Nf3. }
5... O-O
{ In the past, people were connecting this move order with the understandable idea of not being a pawn down before they even drew a breath, and winning it back straight away with  5...Nxe4  . However, the position after  6.Nxe4  Bxe5  7.d4  Bg7  8.Bg5!  f6  9.Be3  while not unplayable, is definitely not something I would recommend.  Our compensation is of course based on the tempi we will win chasing the  Ne5  back, and the open e-file. We're also threatening  ...Nxe4  here. However, White hasn't really sinned against the chess principles too much in the four developing moves that were made so far, and the one capture − meaning we can't expect an easy ride. White has a number of viable options: }
6. Nf3
{ White removes the knight from its vulnerable post in an attempt to hold on to the e4-pawn. After  6...Re8  , there are three major ways to do so and we will deal with all of them independently. }
6... Re8 7. d3
{ 7.Be2  Nxe4  transposes to a variation covered in the6th move Alternatives chapter. }
7... d5 8. cxd5 Nxd5
{ The text move is a lot more ambitious since Black will eventually have to either spend time moving the Nd5 out of the way or take on c3, improving White's structure and solving the problem with the d4-square. }
9. Bd2 Bg4
{ It's very important to generate a lot of counterplay straight away. If White gets to finish development, we'll be in trouble. }
10. Qb3 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Na6
{ A very important move − for now, we're creating a threat of ...Nc5, but we're also preparing for counterplay with ...c5-c4, if need be, as you will see in the12.Be3 lines. As is often the case in the 4...e5 line, we can't afford to take one backward step or to make one slow move. }
12. Be3 c5
{ The only good way of continuing to create immediate threats, but the idea of ...c5-c4 is extremely awkward for White here. }
13. Rc1 Rc8 { Renewing the threat. } 14. Nd2
{ The knight move doesn't actually prevent the opening of the files. } 14... c4
{ Freeing up the c5-square for the knight. } 15. Nxc4 Nc5 16. Bxc5 Rxc5
{ Having traded the Be3 which was doing an excellent job gluing White's position together, we’re now ready to attack the weakened pawns. }
17. Be2 Bh6 { Forcing the rook away from its best square. } 18. Rb1 Be6
{ And now we’re switching back to e6, which will win back the important e4-pawn. }
19. O-O Bxc4 20. dxc4 Rxe4
{ With equality − the extra c-pawn will be irrelevant due to our active pieces and the opposite-colored bishops. }
