{ Freeing up the c5-square for the knight. } 15. Nxc4 Nc5 16. Bxc5 Rxc5
{ Having traded the Be3 which was doing an excellent job gluing White's position together, we’re now ready to attack the weakened pawns. }
17. Be2 Bh6 { Forcing the rook away from its best square. } 18. Rd1
{ 18.Ne3  Bxe3  19.fxe3  Bxe2  20.Kxe2  Qg5  is similar to the main line, where  the moves Rd1 and ...b5 have been included. Here too, Black's compensation against the king in the center and White's soft pawn structure gives us a good game.  Additionally, not having the pawn on b5 offers us the possibility to sometimes activate our rooks along the b-file. This is visible if we continue  21.g3  Re6!  preparing ...Rb5 or ...Rb6. }
18... Bxe2 19. Kxe2 b5
{ Now that the rook left the c1-square, and we control it by having the bishop on h6, we push the Nc4 away and are prepared to put pressure on the c3-pawn. Of course, the white king being stuck in the center is a very large part of the reason why we’re fine here, despite being two pawns down. }
20. Ne3 { The most sensible option, trying to blunt the impact of the Bh6. }
20... Bxe3 21. fxe3 Qg5
{ We have plenty of play vs. the softened structure. The g2-pawn is hanging, we can also attack the c3-pawn with ...Rec8 next, and if the Rh1 leaves its post we can win the h2-pawn with ...Qh5+. White will struggle to establish any kind of control in this position. }
