{ I believe this move is stronger than what we've previously seen. } 16... Nc5
{ Our plan is simple: we want ...Qf6, ...Rad8, and ...Ne6 when the knight gets pushed away from c5 where it's currently being a source of major annoyance for White. The best setup to counter our dark squares dominance is probably Qd2 and then f4, but then White has to worry about ...Nb3 constantly.  White is, of course, very interested in opening up the h-file, something we can't really prevent, and then, in an ideal scenario, continue breaking apart our K-side defenses with f4-f5. }
17. Qc2 { 17.Rc1  Ne6  transposes to the14.h4 variation. } 17... Ne6 18. Qd2
{ Losing a tempo but making sure the Qd2/f4 setup materializes. } 18... Qf6 19.
f4 Rad8 20. h5 Nc5 { With double threats of ...Nb3 and ...Bxe3. } 21. Rd1 Bxe3
{ With this trade, we're making sure White can't recapture with the pawn. } 22.
Qxe3 Ne6 { Now the f4-pawn will have to be returned. } 23. hxg6 fxg6 24. f5
gxf5 25. e5 Qg7 26. d4 Kh8
{ With a very strange position where both kings don't feel particularly safe, and the engines proclaim the week of dynamic equality. }
