13. Ne2 { Retreating the knight is less problematic for us. } 13... Bg4
{ As usual, we're very happy provoking f3 so that we have more sources of counterplay with the softened white K-side and the g1-a7 diagonal open. }
14. Rb1 Qe7
{ A nice combo move − protecting b7 and opening up the d8-square for the rook. }
15. h3 Bxe2 16. Qxe2 Bxc3
{ Having won the pawn back, we're doing quite well, e.g. } 17. f4 Nd4 18. Qg4
Rad8 19. e5 a6
{ We want to play ...Ne6 next and stopping Bb5 in advance makes a lot of sense. }
20. Be3 Ne6 21. Be4 Bd4
{ And we're fine. For instance, after  22.Bxd4  Rxd4  White is unable to play  23.Rxb7  since  23...Qc5  and the subsequent discovered check will win the house. }
