[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. English 1.c4 g6 2.e4 e5 3.Nf3"]
[Black "English 2.e4 e5 3.Nc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
{ The English is easily a topic for a full LTR, but I'll try to show you a way to cut down on the number of options White can choose against us. }
1... g6
{ Just as all those years ago, I'm recommending this somewhat rare move as a reply. In most cases, we will transpose back into classical English setups, but by choosing this move, we're locking White out of some of the lines they could try forcing on us. }
2. e4 e5
{ Another important point − we're not planning to be forced into playing the King's Indian, that should always be a choice you make of your own free will. }
3. Nc3
{ An option I used to ignore in the past, but won't for this course after being reminded of it by the diligent beta testers.  By playing this way @@StartBracket@@and it's worth noting the c4/g3/e4 systems have been around for a while, at least since Botvinnik's days@@EndBracket@@, White is giving up on the idea of playing d2-d4 quickly and plans to finish development before combining ideas of b4-b5, Be3 and d3-d4 and f4.  Despite its historic pedigree, this plan is far from popular these days. I will provide you with a solid option against it, without going too in-depth. }
3... Bg7 4. g3 c5
{ Anish played this, so it can't be bad. The idea is that the e5/d6/c5 systems are quite playable even when White goes for a useful move instead of e4? − so they're definitely fine when we're actually just mirroring White's development.   As an alternative, I wanted to suggest we follow in Garry's footsteps:  4...Nc6  5.Bg2  d6  6.Nge2  Nge7  7.O-O  O-O  8.d3  Nd4!?  , but after  9.Nxd4  exd4  10.Ne2!  which is much stronger than  10.Nd5  that Gulko played against Kasparov in 1995, I don't believe we have equality. }
5. d3 d6 6. Bg2 Nc6 7. Nge2 Nge7 8. O-O O-O
{ These moves should happen in most cases, so we're getting this out of the way. }
9. a3
{ This can be met by continuing to be boring @@StartBracket@@generally, not a very exciting line as you may have gathered@@EndBracket@@. }
9... a6 10. Rb1 Rb8 11. b4 cxb4 12. axb4 b5 { We're in no way worse. } *

