[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. English 1.c4 g6 2.e4 e5 3.Nf3"]
[Black "English 2.e4 e5 3.Nf3 − 6.Bd3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
{ The English is easily a topic for a full LTR, but I'll try to show you a way to cut down on the number of options White can choose against us. }
1... g6
{ Just as all those years ago, I'm recommending this somewhat rare move as a reply. In most cases, we will transpose back into classical English setups, but by choosing this move, we're locking White out of some of the lines they could try forcing on us. }
2. e4 e5
{ Another important point − we're not planning to be forced into playing the King's Indian, that should always be a choice you make of your own free will. }
3. Nf3 { White allows us to get a better grip on the center by normal means. }
3... Bg7 4. d4
{ I had an online game against Nepomniachtchi who played  4.Nc3  instead, which I believe to be inaccurate in view of  4...Nc6  ,  stopping d4 for the time being. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6
{ I will note that  5...Nc6  6.Nxc6  bxc6  is also entirely playable, but I like the text move better since it allows us to engage White in an immediate fight in the center.   Our plan will be to castle and then push for ...c6 and ...d5 @@StartBracket@@and in many cases, actually ...d5! followed by ...c6 once White takes@@EndBracket@@ in order to save a tempo on ...d7-d6 altogether. }
6. Bd3
{ An attempt to make sure the king can get out of the center asap, but it has drawbacks. }
6... O-O 7. O-O d5
{ Faster than starting with  7...c6  −  the fact that the bishop is on d3, in the way of the Qd1, means we can use the unprotected Nd4 to speed up our central play even more. }
8. cxd5 c6 { This is, of course, the justification for the previous move. } 9.
h3
{ Taking the g4-square away and planning to meet  9...cxd5  with  10.e5  , which is interesting, but we're OK. }
9... cxd5 10. e5 Ne4 11. f4 f6 { Undermining the center right way. } 12. Be3
fxe5 13. fxe5 Rxf1+ 14. Qxf1 Nc6
{ Play remains unclear. Note that the greedy  14...Bxe5  15.Bxe4  dxe4  16.Qc4+  followed by Nc3, gives White a dangerous lead in development and should be avoided. }
