{ I had an online game against Nepomniachtchi who played  4.Nc3  instead, which I believe to be inaccurate in view of  4...Nc6  ,  stopping d4 for the time being. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6
{ I will note that  5...Nc6  6.Nxc6  bxc6  is also entirely playable, but I like the text move better since it allows us to engage White in an immediate fight in the center.   Our plan will be to castle and then push for ...c6 and ...d5 @@StartBracket@@and in many cases, actually ...d5! followed by ...c6 once White takes@@EndBracket@@ in order to save a tempo on ...d7-d6 altogether. }
6. Nc3
{ 6.e5?!  Ne4  is  not great for White at all − the pawn on e5 becomes a target. }
6... O-O
{ As usual, we're trying to launch an attack on the white center asap, meaning we don't waste time on pawn moves unless they're ...d7-d5, or preparing ...d7-d5. }
7. Be3
{ Somewhat shockingly, I believe this is the only way for White to pose any kind of a problem. }
7... c6
{ Shockingly, the inclusion of  7...Re8  8.Bd3  is heavily in White's favor, the difference being  8...c6  9.O-O  d5  10.cxd5  cxd5  11.Bb5!  We're forced to play  11...Rf8  , and are very sad about it. }
8. e5
{ The most principled reaction, in particular because of what the follow-up is.   A@@EndBracket@@  8.Bd3  d5  is a good version of the usual lines.   B@@EndBracket@@  8.Nb3  Re8  is very incongruous play by White.   C@@EndBracket@@  8.c5  Re8  9.f3  b6  is also going to be good for us.  Once the c5-pawn is removed, our ...d5 breaks gain in strength. }
8... Ne8 9. Nf3 d6 10. Be2 Qa5 11. exd6 Nxd6
{ Using the fact that White isn't fully developed yet gives us a good game. } *

