[White "12. Symmetrical English 1.c4 g6 2.Nf3"]
[Black "Symmetrical English 1.c4 g6 2.Nf3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
{ The English is easily a topic for a full LTR, but I'll try to show you a way to cut down on the number of options White can choose against us. }
1... g6
{ Just as all those years ago, I'm recommending this somewhat rare move as a reply. In most cases, we will transpose back into classical English setups, but by choosing this move, we're locking White out of some of the lines they could try forcing on us. }
2. Nf3
{ A@@EndBracket@@  2.d4  Nf6  is, of course, a transposition into our beloved Grünfeld.   B@@EndBracket@@  2.g3  c5  3.Bg2  Bg7  will eventually transpose into the 2.Nc3 c5 lines regardless of which moves come next since  White can’t really do without Nc3.  We use the 2...c5 move order because after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppp1p/6p1/8/2P5/6P1/PP1PPP1P/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Bg7  3.d4  may not allow us to play  symmetrical ...c6 systems @@StartBracket@@Part 1@@EndBracket@@ comfortably. }
2... Bg7 3. Nc3 { 3.d4  Nf6  is the Grünfeld again. } 3... c5
{ This is very often going to be the point of 1...g6. By postponing ...Nf6, we're making it much less comfortable for White to push for systems where they're playing an early d2-d4 by focusing our attention on that square. For instance, here we're happy to meet 4.d4, which will be discussed later on. }
4. d4 { 4.g3  Nc6  5.Bg2  transposes to the2.Nc3 line. } 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6
{ Because of this move, immediately attacking the Nd4, White is unable to get e4 and Be3 in, basically not reaching the desired Maroczy setup. That's why we choose this particular move order and leave the knight on g8 for now. }
6. Nc2
{ 6.e3  Nf6  ,  planning ...O-O and ...d5, is very safe. As mentioned already, without the pawn on e4, White's setup isn't very threatening. }
6... Bxc3+
{ Other quieter moves are also possible, but this is a very direct way of utilizing our additional options. }
7. bxc3 Nf6 8. f3
{ White should be fighting for control of the central squares quite hard here. }
8... Qa5 9. e4 d6
{ We wait for White to play 10.Ne3 before capturing on c3. That is because  9...Qxc3+  10.Bd2  forces our  queen to e5 instead of a3, which is preferable. }
10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O Be6
{ We're ready to push against the c3/c4 pair with ...Ne5 and ...Rac8, and if White aims to get the knight to d5, we can take one of them and then start trading. }
12. Ne3
{ After  12.Rb1  we should avoid getting our queen trapped with  12...Qxa2  13.Na3!  But most other 12th moves are sufficient, for instance, @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp2pp1p/2npbnp1/q7/2P1P3/2P2P2/P1N1B1PP/1RBQ1RK1 b - - 5 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Rab8  or the sharper  12...Rfc8  . }
12... Qxc3 13. Rb1 Qd4
{ In my opinion, the simplest continuation, which will either get the queens off or severely hinder White's plans due to the pinned Ne3. }
*

