1. c4
{ The English is easily a topic for a full LTR, but I'll try to show you a way to cut down on the number of options White can choose against us. }
1... g6
{ Just as all those years ago, I'm recommending this somewhat rare move as a reply. In most cases, we will transpose back into classical English setups, but by choosing this move, we're locking White out of some of the lines they could try forcing on us. }
2. Nc3
{ A@@EndBracket@@  2.d4  Nf6  is, of course, a transposition into our beloved Grünfeld.   B@@EndBracket@@  2.g3  c5  3.Bg2  Bg7  will eventually lead to 2.Nc3 c5 lines regardless of which moves come next since  White can’t really do without Nc3. }
2... c5 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 Nc6
{ The starting position of the symmetrical c4/c5 English. White's main option here, by far, is  5.Nf3  , but these days you have to be ready for many other attempts, including some very quirky ones, such as  5.b3  . }
5. e4
{ This somewhat strange setup is not bad at all, especially if we don't react to it properly and allow White to play Nge2, d3, h3, Be3 and start pushing for d3-d4. }
5... a6
{ I like starting with this move − the threat of ...b5 is quite real and White is more or less obliged to further weaken the structure. }
6. a4
{ White needs to prevent ...b7-b5 since after, for instance,  6.Nge2  b5  7.cxb5  axb5  8.Nxb5  Ba6  , Black has very good Benko-style compensation. }
6... d6 7. d3 Nf6 8. h3
{ If White tries to stop ...Bg4 by playing 8.h3, we can go for the plan of rerouting the f6-knight. }
8... Nd7 9. Nge2 Nf8
{ Landing the knight on e6 before White had time to play Be3 and d4. } *

