{ This move was played against me by Haik Martirosyan in the Riga GS, but I don't think it does very much, and I actually quite like my reaction. }
5... Nf6
{ 5...e6  is not bad, but it does improve White's  6.e4  setups since we'd prefer not to play ...e6 there. }
6. e4 { The database informed me I played 6.e4 anyway :@@EndBracket@@ } 6... d6
7. Nge2 O-O 8. h3 a6
{ Note that the ultra-fast play with ...a6 and ...b5 we've chosen vs. 5.e4 doesn't work as well here since White constantly has the e4-e5 counter push which we avoided by playing ...a6 with the knight back on g8 in the5.e4 variation. }
9. Be3 Bd7 10. O-O Rb8
{ Black was still perfectly fine in Svidler-Grischuk, chess.com 2020. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13. Symmetrical English 2.Nc3 − 5th move Alternatives"]
[Black "Symmetrical English 2.Nc3 − 5.d3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
{ The English is easily a topic for a full LTR, but I'll try to show you a way to cut down on the number of options White can choose against us. }
1... g6
{ Just as all those years ago, I'm recommending this somewhat rare move as a reply. In most cases, we will transpose back into classical English setups, but by choosing this move, we're locking White out of some of the lines they could try forcing on us. }
2. Nc3
{ A@@EndBracket@@  2.d4  Nf6  is, of course, a transposition into our beloved Grünfeld.   B@@EndBracket@@  2.g3  c5  3.Bg2  Bg7  will eventually lead to 2.Nc3 c5 lines regardless of which moves come next since  White can’t really do without Nc3. }
2... c5 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 Nc6
{ The starting position of the symmetrical c4/c5 English. White's main option here, by far, is  5.Nf3  , but these days you have to be ready for many other attempts, including some very quirky ones, such as  5.b3  . }
5. d3
{ This move was played against me by Haik Martirosyan in the Riga GS, but I don't think it does very much, and I actually quite like my reaction. }
5... Nf6
{ 5...e6  is not bad, but it does improve White's  6.e4  setups since we'd prefer not to play ...e6 there. }
6. e3 e6 7. Nge2 O-O 8. O-O b6
{ I chose to develop the bishop before we play ...d5 so that we don't have to worry about Nf4 too much. }
9. a3 Bb7 10. b4 d5 { Launching a timely counterstrike in the center. } 11.
bxc5 dxc4 12. d4 bxc5 13. Rb1 Qe7
{ Not fearing  14.dxc5  Na5  when Black has a seizable advantage. } 14. Qa4
Rac8 { Playing this way doesn't work out for White. } *

