[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. Symmetrical English 2.Nc3 − 5.Nf3 Main Line"]
[Black "Symmetrical English 5.Nf3 e6 6.h4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
{ The English is easily a topic for a full LTR, but I'll try to show you a way to cut down on the number of options White can choose against us. }
1... g6
{ Just as all those years ago, I'm recommending this somewhat rare move as a reply. In most cases, we will transpose back into classical English setups, but by choosing this move, we're locking White out of some of the lines they could try forcing on us. }
2. Nc3
{ A@@EndBracket@@  2.d4  Nf6  is, of course, a transposition into our beloved Grünfeld.   B@@EndBracket@@  2.g3  c5  3.Bg2  Bg7  will eventually transpose into the 2.Nc3 c5 lines regardless of which moves come next since  White can’t really do without Nc3.  We use the 2...c5 move order because after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppp1p/6p1/8/2P5/6P1/PP1PPP1P/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...Bg7  3.d4  may not allow us to play  symmetrical ...c6 systems @@StartBracket@@Part 1@@EndBracket@@ comfortably. }
2... c5 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 Nc6
{ The starting position of the symmetrical c4/c5 English. White's main option here, by far, is  5.Nf3  , but these days you have to be ready for many other attempts, including some very quirky ones, such as  5.b3  . }
5. Nf3 e6
{ After some deliberation, I'm sticking with the recommendation I gave in the chess24 series. Honorable mentions go to  5...d6  6.O-O  Bf5  and  6...e6  . }
6. h4 { As always, this is a very sensible idea but we're not flustered. } 6...
h6
{ A@@EndBracket@@  6...d5  7.h5  Nge7  8.d3  was a bit better for White in Adams-Wei Yi, Wijk aan Zee 2016.   B@@EndBracket@@  6...Nf6  7.d4  cxd4  8.Nxd4  also justifies h4 quite well since we're very much in the 'let's not allow White an easy d4' business in this line. }
7. e3 Nge7 8. d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 d5 10. cxd5
{ This was played in two Carlsen-So games on chess24 in 2020, but Wesley played the safer  10...Nxd5  and  10...Nxd4  in those, while I prefer the text move. }
10... exd5 11. O-O O-O 12. Re1
{ Now either  12...Re8  or even  12...h5  ,  intending ...Bg4, gives Black an easy game. }
12... Re8 13. Bd2 Nxd4
{ A good moment to clarify the situation in the center now that the bishop has been committed to d2. }
14. exd4 Be6
{ We have a typical symmetrical and equal position. Next up, we want to play ...Qd7 and ...Nf5, deploying all our pieces to their ideal squares. }
*

