10. O-O O-O 11. Bf4 a6 12. Nc3 Re8 13. Bg5 h6 14. Be3
{ This is a weird way to sidestep our intended counterplay with ...Nh5, but we can't be too sad about White wasting so much time faffing about with that bishop. }
14... Ng4 { 14...h5!?  is also interesting. } 15. Nxc6 bxc6 16. Bd4 Ne5 17. Na4
{ There was a time White was considered to have a nice static advantage in these types of positions. Nowadays, activity is factored in better. The old wisdom should serve as a word of warning though, if we play too tamely and allow some pieces to get exchanged, White may indeed be able to nurture that structural advantage. }
17... Bf5 18. h3 Rb8 19. b3 h5
{ We have one more unclear Tarrasch-like position on our hands. To illustrate my point on move 17, after the natural  20.Qd2  , we can play  20...Qc8!?  with the idea to either exchange bishops on h3 or  , after  21.Kh2  , continue  21...h4!  22.g4  Bxg4  23.hxg4  Nxg4+  24.Kg1  Qc7  25.f4  Bxd4+  26.Qxd4  a5!  when we are a piece down yet super active and already for choice. }
