1. d4 Nf6 2. f3
{ This is not a good move, just ask Ben Finegold. In this position, I can only really 'justify' it by suggesting White can get the Blackmar-Diemer this way, but how much of an actual justification this is, is very much open to debate. }
2... d5 { Of course we're not allowing e4. } 3. e4
{ 3.Nc3  c5  transposes to the2.Nc3 move order. } 3... dxe4
{ We're a pawn up, case closed. Well, not really, but pretty close, to be honest. }
4. Nc3 exf3 5. Nxf3
{ Even more dubious is  5.Qxf3  , the so-called Ryder Gambit. Following  5...Qxd4  6.Be3  Qg4  , we are eager to exchange queens and convert our two extra pawns. White should therefore play  7.Qf2  when the machine indicates  7...Qf5  , but I think  7...e5  8.Nf3  Bb4!  with the idea  9.Nxe5  Qe4  is more practical and, frankly, more or less winning for Black. }
5... c6
{ The most useful semi-waiting move.  5...Bg4?!  is less precise since after  6.h3  Bh5  7.g4  Bg6  8.Qe2!  with h4 to follow, White actually does develop a decent initiative. }
6. Bc4 Bf5 7. Ne5
{ More aggressive than castling kingside but not any better. } 7... e6 8. g4
{ 8.O-O  transposes to the next variation with 7.O-O. } 8... Nfd7
{ An important resource as  8...Bg6  9.h4  is much less clear. } 9. gxf5
{ A@@EndBracket@@  9.Nxd7  Qh4+  10.Kf1  Bxg4  loses.   B@@EndBracket@@  9.Nxf7  Qh4+  is no improvement either. }
9... Nxe5 10. dxe5 Qh4+ { We win back the piece and then the game. } *

