1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 { Threatening 3.e4, so our reply is semi-forced here. } 2...
d5
{ The big negative effect of playing Nc3 so early, with the pawn back on c2, is that White won't be able to challenge our center with c4 any time soon. And for that very same reason, we're even happier than usual pushing ...c5 ourselves. }
3. Bg5
{ The Veresov Attack proper, so to speak. It's ambitious, but also, happily for us, not very good. White definitely can @@StartBracket@@and should@@EndBracket@@ go back to London-related things with  3.Bf4  . We can respond with  3...g6  − see therelevant chapter, to keep continuity throughout the course, or opt for  3...c5  , which is a safe backupline. }
3... Nbd7
{ A very solid move, combining defense against the spoilation of our kingside pawn structure with preparation for the ...c5 break.   Note that  3...e6?  4.e4  commits the unforgivable sin of suddenly making us play the French. }
4. Qd2 h6 5. Bh4 e6
{ Followed by ...c5, is already somewhat better for us since White really isn't doing anything and that Nc3 is sticking out like a sore thumb. }
