d5
{ The big negative effect of playing Nc3 so early, with the pawn back on c2, is that White won't be able to challenge our center with c4 any time soon. And for that very same reason, we're even happier than usual pushing ...c5 ourselves. }
3. Bg5
{ The Veresov Attack proper, so to speak. It's ambitious, but also, happily for us, not very good. White definitely can @@StartBracket@@and should@@EndBracket@@ go back to London-related things with  3.Bf4  . We can respond with  3...g6  − see therelevant chapter, to keep continuity throughout the course, or opt for  3...c5  , which is a safe backupline. }
3... Nbd7
{ A very solid move, combining defense against the spoilation of our kingside pawn structure with preparation for the ...c5 break.   Note that  3...e6?  4.e4  commits the unforgivable sin of suddenly making us play the French. }
4. Qd3
{ This move has been played by some good players, Hikaru among them, but it's not very good. }
4... h6
{ 4...c5  is played much more often and leads to positions that are good for Black, but the text move is more efficient. }
5. Bxf6 Nxf6 6. e4 dxe4 7. Nxe4 g6
{ We show flexibility in our approach to the position, preparing to develop the bishop to g7 and not minding an exchange on f6. }
8. Nxf6+ exf6
{ The structure is now reminiscent of the Classical Caro-Kann variation with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/8/3PN3/8/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nxf6+  exf6  but with the difference that White has lost the bishop pair, which is a pretty big deal. Black is in good shape. }
9. O-O-O Bd6
{ Once again we're doing very well with our bishop pair in a reasonably open position. Note that now that the structure has changed, we develop our bishop to d6, instead of g7.   If White attempts to disturb us from castling K-side by playing  10.Re1+  , that would help even further since after  10...Kf8  ,  the king will be tucked away on g7. }
