[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17. London System 2.Bf4 g6 3.Nc3 − 4th moves"]
[Black "London 3.Nc3 d5 4.e3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ The dreaded London. I have now spent quite a bit of time trying to figure it out for the course, and I can tell you my intense hatred for it has only increased. }
2... g6
{ We're playing 2...g6 for one major reason. White can start with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/5n2/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  , and as honorable Grünfeld aficionados, we're obliged to reply with  2...g6  , which, after  3.Bf4  , locks us into the fianchetto setups. Therefore, I feel that spending time to learn the other replies to 2.Bf4 is, let's say, an unnecessary investment of time and effort on both mine and your part. }
3. Nc3
{ 3.f3?!  is a very odd move here, and we should welcome it wholeheartedly.  3...d5  4.Nc3  c5  .  The plan of pushing e4 is dead and with it so is any justification for 3.f3. }
3... d5 4. e3 Bg7 5. h4 { This is a reasonably popular sideline. } 5... h5
{ There's no reason to even contemplate something like  5...O-O  6.h5  Nxh5?  7.Rxh5  . }
6. Be2
{ Too slow − after  6.Nb5  Na6  7.Nc3  , we probably should play  7...Nb8  and wink at our opponent. But the engines suggest playing @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp1ppb1/n4np1/3p3p/3P1B1P/2N1P3/PPP2PP1/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...O-O  8.Bxa6  bxa6  9.Be5  c6  @@StartBracket@@followed by ...Bh6, unpinning ourselves@@EndBracket@@, which is not bad either. }
6... O-O 7. Nf3 c5 8. dxc5 Qa5
{ We're winning the pawn back with a comfortable game. } 9. O-O Qxc5 10. Nb5 a6
11. Nc7 Ra7 12. a3 Bf5
{ This move provides us with easily enough cover against the threat of b4. }
13. Nd4 Bg4 { Provoking f3 is always useful. } 14. f3 Bd7
{ Black is fine. White should probably ask for repetition with  15.Nb3  Qc6  16.Nd4  , and it’s on us to choose whether to allow it or perhaps play on with  16...Qb6  . }
*

