21. fxg4 Ne3
{ White is just in time to create counterplay, forcing us to set up a perpetual. }
22. Rd2 { Avoiding the perpetual but missing a more pressing issue. } 22...
Nxg4 { This is why we included ...hxg4, fxg4 earlier. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17. London System 2.Bf4 g6 3.Nc3 − 4th moves"]
[Black "London 3.Nc3 d5 4.e3 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ The dreaded London. I have now spent quite a bit of time trying to figure it out for the course, and I can tell you my intense hatred for it has only increased. }
2... g6
{ We're playing 2...g6 for one major reason. White can start with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/5n2/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  , and as honorable Grünfeld aficionados, we're obliged to reply with  2...g6  , which, after  3.Bf4  , locks us into the fianchetto setups. Therefore, I feel that spending time to learn the other replies to 2.Bf4 is, let's say, an unnecessary investment of time and effort on both mine and your part. }
3. Nc3
{ 3.f3?!  is a very odd move here, and we should welcome it wholeheartedly.  3...d5  4.Nc3  c5  .  The plan of pushing e4 is dead and with it so is any justification for 3.f3. }
3... d5 4. e3 Bg7 5. h4 { This is a reasonably popular sideline. } 5... h5
{ There's no reason to even contemplate something like  5...O-O  6.h5  Nxh5?  7.Rxh5  . }
6. Nf3
{ After  6.Nb5  Na6  7.Nc3  , we probably should play  7...Nb8  and wink at our opponent. But the engines suggest playing  7...O-O  8.Bxa6  bxa6  9.Be5  c6  @@StartBracket@@followed by ...Bh6, unpinning ourselves@@EndBracket@@, which is not bad either. }
6... O-O 7. Ne5 c5 8. Qd2 cxd4 9. exd4 Nc6 10. f3 Nd7
{ We're aiming to deal with the Ne5 straight away.  10...Bf5  is much more popular and quite playable, but I like the text move more. }
11. Nxd5 Ndxe5 12. dxe5 Bf5
{ 12...Nxe5  13.O-O-O  is less precise, Inarkiev-Volokitin, Doha 2016. } 13.
O-O-O Rc8
{ Now we are very seriously threatening ...Nxe5.  13...Nxe5  is possible, but  13...Rc8  is cleaner, I believe. }
14. Bg5 { 14.Ne3  Be6  and we'll  collect the e5-pawn with good play. } 14...
Bxe5 15. Bc4 Na5 { This striking move gives us immediate equality. } 16. Nxe7+
{ The only move. } 16... Qxe7 17. Bxe7 Nxc4
{ Who can resist sacrificing the queen in this way?! Despite having just two pieces, Black's attack is raging. }
18. Qg5 f6 19. Qh6 Rf7 20. g4
{ Once again the only move, since ...Rh7 was a very big threat. } 20... hxg4
21. fxg4 Ne3
{ White is just in time to create counterplay, forcing us to set up a perpetual. }
22. gxf5 Rxc2+ 23. Kb1 Rxb2+ 24. Kc1 Rc2+ { With a draw by perpetual check. } *

