{ If case of  7.Qd2  c5  ,  followed by ...Nc6 @@StartBracket@@and then we will even have a choice of sides to castle to@@EndBracket@@, is completely fine for us. The text move is aiming to exploit the fact that our bishop might not have too many squares once we take on c2, but we can work around that. }
7... Bxc2 8. g4 { Cutting off the return. } 8... c5 9. e3
{ The only move − White needs to keep the pawn on d4 alive at all costs, or the bishop will escape quite easily. }
9... Nc6 10. Bb5
{ This is wrong since once that bishop gets traded, we will have access to the d3-square. }
10... a6 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. Kd2 { 12.Rc1  Bd3  lets the bishop off the hook. }
12... cxd4 13. exd4 c5 14. Kxc2 cxd4 15. Nce2 Qc7+
{ We have tremendous play for the piece. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17. London System 2.Bf4 g6 3.Nc3 − 4th moves"]
[Black "London 3.Nc3 d5 4.Qd2 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ The dreaded London. I have now spent quite a bit of time trying to figure it out for the course, and I can tell you my intense hatred for it has only increased. }
2... g6
{ We're playing 2...g6 for one major reason. White can start with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/5n2/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  , and as honorable Grünfeld aficionados, we're obliged to reply with  2...g6  , which, after  3.Bf4  , locks us into the fianchetto setups. Therefore, I feel that spending time to learn the other replies to 2.Bf4 is, let's say, an unnecessary investment of time and effort on both mine and your part. }
3. Nc3
{ 3.f3?!  is a very odd move here, and we should welcome it wholeheartedly.  3...d5  4.Nc3  c5  .  The plan of pushing e4 is dead and with it so is any justification for 3.f3. }
3... d5 4. Qd2
{ A logical move, intending both Bh6 and O-O-O, but as you will see, actually castling long is likely to cause White grief, and Bh6 can be dealt with quite easily. }
4... Bg7 5. Bh6 Bxh6
{ 5...O-O  is also fine, but the text move is more concrete. } 6. Qxh6 Bf5 7.
f3
{ If case of  7.Qd2  c5  ,  followed by ...Nc6 @@StartBracket@@and then we will even have a choice of sides to castle to@@EndBracket@@, is completely fine for us. The text move is aiming to exploit the fact that our bishop might not have too many squares once we take on c2, but we can work around that. }
7... Bxc2 8. g4 { Cutting off the return. } 8... c5 9. e3
{ The only move − White needs to keep the pawn on d4 alive at all costs, or the bishop will escape quite easily. }
9... Nc6 10. Rc1 cxd4 11. exd4 Nxd4 12. Nb5
{ This clever move actually does win the piece for White, but we have a very nice way of dealing with that problem. }
12... g5
{ Cutting the queen off the d2-square, opening up g6 for the bishop, and also, as will become clear in a moment, opening up the 6th rank for very useful tactics. }
13. Qxg5 Ne6
{ The pawn grab loses on the spot since the bishop will now escape and White's position is in ruins. }
*

