15. Qxd5+ e6 16. Qb5 Qxb5 17. Bxb5 Rxd4 18. Rc1 Nc6
{ The most energetic way to meet the threat of Rxc8+. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. London System 3.Nd2 & 3.Nf3 Introduction"]
[Black "London 3.Nd2 − 5.Ngf3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ The dreaded London. I have now spent quite a bit of time trying to figure it out for the course, and I can tell you my intense hatred for it has only increased. }
2... g6
{ We're playing 2...g6 for one major reason. White can start with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/5n2/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  , and as honorable Grünfeld aficionados, we're obliged to reply with  2...g6  , which, after  3.Bf4  , locks us into the fianchetto setups. Therefore, I feel that spending time to learn the other replies to 2.Bf4 is, let's say, an unnecessary investment of time and effort on both mine and your part. }
3. Nd2
{ 3.f3?!  is a very odd move here, and we should welcome it wholeheartedly.  3...d5  4.Nc3  c5  .  The plan of pushing e4 is dead and with it so is any justification for 3.f3. }
3... Bg7 4. e4 O-O
{ We don't need to worry about e5 and we do want to preserve the option of playing ...d5 in one move. }
5. Ngf3 d5
{ I don't quite like  5...d6  6.c3  Nc6  7.Be2!  when the ...e5 break isn't available and we are forced to make awkward moves like ...Qe8. I'm not too happy about it. In view of that, I'm recommending a different path. }
6. e5 Nh5 { 6...Nfd7  7.h4  is very unclear and could get quite dangerous. } 7.
Be3 c5
{ The Nh5 looks awkward, but we will be developing a lot of play against the white center. }
8. c3 { In case of  8.dxc5  Nc6  and White  cannot save the e5-pawn. } 8... f6
{ 8...cxd4  is a safer option, but White has an interesting way to create additional issues:  9.cxd4  f6  10.Bb5!?   Instead,  10.Be2  transposes to 8...f6.  10.Bb5  is of course aimed at making the  development of the Nb8 a bit more awkward.  And very importantly,  10...Qb6  can now be met with  11.Qb3  . In view of all that I prefer 8...f6. }
9. Bb5 fxe5 10. Nxe5 Qb6 11. Ba4
{ 11.Qb3?  c4!  is an extremely important detail. } 11... cxd4 12. cxd4 Qa6
{ The position is very unclear yet again, e.g. } 13. Qb3 Nf4 14. Bxf4 Rxf4
{ This looks bad at first because d5 is hanging with check, but the line continues! }
15. Rc1 Be6 16. Bb5 Qa5 17. Nf3 Rxf3 18. gxf3 Bxd4
{ From this position, we wish our opponents good luck surviving this mess. } *

