1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ The dreaded London. I have now spent quite a bit of time trying to figure it out for the course, and I can tell you my intense hatred for it has only increased. }
2... g6
{ We're playing 2...g6 for one major reason. White can start with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/5n2/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  , and as honorable Grünfeld aficionados, we're obliged to reply with  2...g6  , which, after  3.Bf4  , locks us into the fianchetto setups. Therefore, I feel that spending time to learn the other replies to 2.Bf4 is, let's say, an unnecessary investment of time and effort on both mine and your part. }
3. Nf3
{ 3.f3?!  is a very odd move here, and we should welcome it wholeheartedly.  3...d5  4.Nc3  c5  .  The plan of pushing e4 is dead and with it so is any justification for 3.f3. }
3... Bg7 4. c3
{ I almost missed this move order, naively assuming this will always transpose into something we already cover in the chapter. In fact, this is quite tricky and requires the type of reply we haven't really made use of elsewhere. We're still fine, though. }
4... d6
{ Note that the issue here is  4...O-O  5.Nbd2!  and neither  5...c5  6.dxc5!  Na6  7.Nb3  , nor @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppppppbp/5np1/8/3P1B2/2P2N2/PP1NPPPP/R2QKB1R b KQ - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...d6  6.e4  are entirely ideal @@StartBracket@@I've mentioned this in the notes to 4.Nbd2@@EndBracket@@. }
5. Nbd2
{ Not such a great decision since we get a gold-plated opportunity to play: }
5... Nh5 6. Bg5 h6 7. Bh4 g5 8. Bg3
{ Now there's a number of nice options, ranging from  8...f5  9.e3  O-O  to the much wilder text move. }
8... g4 9. Nh4 Bf6
{ It turns out the knight on h4 is in trouble in this particular move order. One to remember! }
10. e4 e5 11. Nf5 { The only way for White to keep the knight alive. } 11...
Bxf5 12. dxe5 Nxg3 13. hxg3 Bxe5 14. exf5 h5
{ A very weird and unclear position has arisen, in which we're planning to continue ...Qe7, ...Nd7 and ...O-O-O. }
