1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ The dreaded London. I have now spent quite a bit of time trying to figure it out for the course, and I can tell you my intense hatred for it has only increased. }
2... g6
{ We're playing 2...g6 for one major reason. White can start with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/5n2/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  , and as honorable Grünfeld aficionados, we're obliged to reply with  2...g6  , which, after  3.Bf4  , locks us into the fianchetto setups. Therefore, I feel that spending time to learn the other replies to 2.Bf4 is, let's say, an unnecessary investment of time and effort on both mine and your part. }
3. Nf3
{ 3.f3?!  is a very odd move here, and we should welcome it wholeheartedly.  3...d5  4.Nc3  c5  .  The plan of pushing e4 is dead and with it so is any justification for 3.f3. }
3... Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. Be2
{ Trying to save the tempo White usually spends on h3 is a very worthwhile endeavour - but we can use it to our advantage, too }
5... d6 6. O-O
{ 6.h3  transposes to the5.h3 move order while  6.c3  is also atransposition. }
6... Nh5
{ 6...c5  is not at all unplayable, but why not actually use the fact that h3 is not there yet. }
7. Bg5 h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Nfd2 Nf4
{ Much better than  9...Nf6  10.Bg3  Nc6  11.Nc3  as in Carlsen-Nepomniachtchi, chess24.com 2020. }
10. exf4 gxh4 11. c3 Nd7 12. Nf3 e5
{ Despite the pawn on h4 looking a bit odd, once the position becomes more open, our bishops will start dominating. Notably, White can't win the h4-pawn by trading. }
13. dxe5 dxe5 14. fxe5 Nxe5 15. Qxd8
{ It makes little sense to force this trade for White, giving up the d-file and, essentially, landing in a difficult endgame. }
15... Nxf3+ 16. Bxf3 Rxd8
{ That means our h4-pawn will often get to h3, where, as we all know in this post A0 meta, it's going to be extremely annoying. }
