{ We're playing 2...g6 for one major reason. White can start with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/5n2/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  , and as honorable Grünfeld aficionados, we're obliged to reply with  2...g6  , which, after  3.Bf4  , locks us into the fianchetto setups. Therefore, I feel that spending time to learn the other replies to 2.Bf4 is, let's say, an unnecessary investment of time and effort on both mine and your part. }
3. Nf3
{ 3.f3?!  is a very odd move here, and we should welcome it wholeheartedly.  3...d5  4.Nc3  c5  .  The plan of pushing e4 is dead and with it so is any justification for 3.f3. }
3... Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. c3
{ White's typical pawn formation in this opening, which exemplifies what the line stands for: solid yet not too threatening. Amateur players often feel discouraged when meeting this dry approach as Black but should not despair, there are plenty of active plans at our disposal. }
5... d6 6. Nbd2 Nh5
{ I originally wanted to give  6...c5  here, before @@StartBracket@@very belatedly, in fact@@EndBracket@@ realizing that  7.dxc5!  dxc5  8.h3  leads to a position we're definitely avoiding if White plays  6.h3  . Therefore, we have this slightly weird move order. }
7. Bg5 c5
{ We're still very interested in pushing ...c5 in all of these positions, but it's often quite important to drive the bishop away from the h2-b8 diagonal. }
8. Bd3 { Quite a playable move, for a change. } 8... cxd4 9. cxd4
{ 9.exd4  h6  10.Be3  e5  is good for us, as usual. } 9... h6 10. Bh4 Nc6 11.
O-O
{ Black can switch to a plan we haven't encountered before, helped by the fact that White's development is quite slow, and we have plenty of time to reorganize our pieces. }
11... Be6 12. a3 f5
{ Since we couldn't play ...g5 yet due to Nxg5, Qxh5 and Qh7#, we're switching to a kind of a Dutch setup. Our plan is to play ...Bf7, ...Qd7, and then choose to go for the ...e5 or ...g5 push, or perhaps simply trade the bishops off with ...Bf6. White, in the meantime, might need to spend two tempi playing Nd2-b1-c3 to at least get that piece to a decent square. }
*

