{ The dreaded London. I have now spent quite a bit of time trying to figure it out for the course, and I can tell you my intense hatred for it has only increased. }
2... g6
{ We're playing 2...g6 for one major reason. White can start with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/5n2/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  , and as honorable Grünfeld aficionados, we're obliged to reply with  2...g6  , which, after  3.Bf4  , locks us into the fianchetto setups. Therefore, I feel that spending time to learn the other replies to 2.Bf4 is, let's say, an unnecessary investment of time and effort on both mine and your part. }
3. Nf3
{ 3.f3?!  is a very odd move here, and we should welcome it wholeheartedly.  3...d5  4.Nc3  c5  .  The plan of pushing e4 is dead and with it so is any justification for 3.f3. }
3... Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. h3
{ A major part of White’s game plan in these lines is keeping this bishop alive, and this move provides it with a very safe haven on h2. }
5... d6 6. c3 Nfd7
{ This move order is quite tricky, and it's a rare case of a position where I won't be recommending ...c5.   6...c5  7.dxc5  very importantly, with the pawn already on c3, we no longer have any ...Nd5/...Nh5 tactics to use here.  7...dxc5  8.Nbd2  is a surprisingly annoying position for Black. I wouldn't say we definitely won't equalize in the long run, but I don't really like it and decided to deviate. }
7. Be2 e5 8. Bh2
{ It makes absolutely no sense at all for White to take on e5 since much of the London is built around restrictions placed on our Bg7 by the incredibly solid c3-d4-e3 pawn formation. Suddenly relinquishing that control, giving the c5-square @@StartBracket@@or even e5, after we play ...e5-e4@@EndBracket@@ to the Nd7 by playing 8.dxe5 would go against everything that this opening aims to achieve.  By the same token, the bishop always retreats all the way to h2, since our plan after ...Nfd7 will often involve a serious push on the K-side, and for White to leave themselves open to an additional tempo loss when ...f5-f4 hits the Bg3 would be quite a strange decision. }
8... Nc6
{ Let's talk about the plans here. We're going to be pushing on the kingside, with ...Qe7 and then ...f5, and often ...g5 quite fast, too. White, on the other hand, is likely to try to assume control over the queenside, with a4 and b4 quite likely follow-ups.  One thing we should be mindful of is not allowing White to play c4 and Nc3 too easily − even with a loss of a tempo, this is a good plan if it suddenly becomes available. }
9. a4
{ I believe this is the way to go for White. Pushing this pawn up to a5 @@StartBracket@@or securing the b5-square for the knight if we choose to stop it with ...a5@@EndBracket@@ is quite useful. }
9... f5
{ One of the reasons I quite like starting with a4 before castling here can be seen in a line like  9...a5  10.Na3  Kh8  11.Nb5  e4  12.Nd2  f5  13.g4!  and the fact that the king is not on g1 gives White a lot of additional options. }
10. b4 Qe7 11. b5
{ A notable move because this has been played against Gata Kamsky - the godfather of modern London - himself, and I believe he made a mistake here. }
11... Na5
{ 11...Nd8  12.O-O  Nf7  13.c4!  g5  14.Nc3  is one more example of Black allowing c4/Nc3 and regretting it, Grachev-Kamsky, chess.com 2020. }
12. O-O g5
{ A very unclear position where our knight on a5 is doing a useful job of stopping the Q-side push while our plans on the K-side are still very much in place. }
*

