3... Bg7 4. e3 c5 5. c3 { 5.Nbd2  transposes to the4.Nbd2 move order. } 5...
O-O
{ We're not taking on d4 just yet since it works a lot better once White can't put the knight on c3 after recapturing with the c3-pawn. Therefore, in most cases, we will be waiting for Nbd2 before we do that.   5...Qb6  6.Qb3  d6  ,  with ideas of ...Be6, is playable, but in the end, I chose a different path. }
6. Be2 d6 7. O-O h6 8. Bh4
{ We have a number of options, but I think the simplest is: } 8... cxd4
{ 8...g5  9.Bg3  Ne4  is playable and after  10.a4  or  10.Nbd2  Nxg3  11.hxg3  ,  we should probably play ...Nd7-f6, with an unclear position that the engines prefer for White, but the flexible structure allows us decent counter chances if White overpresses. }
9. cxd4
{ White quite happily takes on d4 with this pawn since it allows Nc3 later, but we're still fine.  9.exd4  Nc6  with ...e5 to follow is good for us. }
9... Qb6 10. Nbd2 Be6 11. Nc4 Qc6 12. Rc1 Rc8
{ This looks strange at first, but there are no good jumps for the Nc4, and we'll play ...Nbd7 next. }
