6. dxc5 Ne4
{ An alternative which leads to the following fairly forced sequence: } 7. Qd5
Nxg5 8. Qxg5 b6 9. Nbd2 Bf6 10. Qd5 Nc6
{ We're going to have good compensation due to our bishop pair and the exposed Qd5. }
11. cxb6 Qxb6 12. Nc4 Qc7
{ Our compensation might seem non-obvious so far, but we'll push the pieces back with ...e6 and ...d5, and it will become much clearer. }
13. Be2 Rb8 14. O-O e6 15. Qd2 d5 16. Na3 Qb6 17. Rab1 Rd8
{ Once we push ...e6-e5, our spatial edge will give us enough for the pawn. } *

