{ I like clarifying the structure as early as possible. It also has the added bonus of removing ideas of Bxf6 and Ne4 from the menu. }
6. exd4 h6
{ I tried a number of other moves here, but I think this is the way to go. We're once again asking White to determine what they want to do with that bishop. Additionally, it's important for us to be able to play ...g6-g5, unpinning the Nf6, if we need it later. }
7. Bxf6
{ Somewhat surprisingly, I believe this is the strongest option for White. }
7... Bxf6 8. Bd3
{ White's gotten rid of what often feels in these lines is the worst piece, and is now planning to play O-O, c3, Re1, and then perhaps try to exploit the softening of our K-side by pushing h4-h5 @@StartBracket@@sometimes White could try this even without castling, but since we can pretty much always meet h4 with ...h5, there is no reason to worry@@EndBracket@@. }
8... d6 9. c3 Nc6
{ 9...O-O  10.h4  h5  is also fine, but not committing to castling yet is more flexible. }
10. h4 d5 { Restricting Nd2. } 11. Nf1 h5 12. Ne3 Qd6
{ We have a perfectly playable position. } *

