[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. 2. Nf3 g6 3.Nbd2"]
[Black "3.Nbd2 c5 4.e3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Nbd2
{ This seemingly innocuous move has gained a lot of popularity in recent years. The point is seen in the line  3...d5  @@StartBracket@@Black does normally want to avoid  allowing e2-e4,  although the option of  3...Bg7  4.e4  d6  , switching to a Pirc, does exist.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/5np1/3p4/3P4/5N2/PPPNPPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  Bg7  5.b4!?  ,  where White will be going for a plan of gaining space on the queenside, heavily discouraging the ...c5 counterplay, and planning to go for c4 later on.  We have a lot of possible options in response, and the one I am proposing has the advantage of putting White's plan under immediate pressure. It can also lead to some very wild complications, which I tend to favor whenever possible in the barrens of the Anti-Grünfeld. }
3... c5
{ As a safer backup plan, I would suggest something along the lines of  3...d5  4.e3  a5!?  I really don't like allowing the b4 space-grab.  5.c4  Bg7  6.b3  O-O  7.Bb2  e6!?  8.Be2  b6  9.O-O  Bb7  ,  aiming to finish development with ...Nbd7, ...Qe7, and then start looking for ...c5. }
4. e3
{ A possible move, of course − but now that the b2-b4 plan is out the window, and ...c5 already played, Black is just instantly fine after any kind of sensible development. }
4... Bg7 5. Bd3 O-O 6. O-O b6 7. c3 Bb7
{ Followed by ...d6 @@StartBracket@@or even ...d5@@EndBracket@@ and ...Nbd7, is of course completely fine for us. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. 2. Nf3 g6 3.Nbd2"]
[Black "3.Nbd2 c5 4.dxc5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Nbd2
{ This seemingly innocuous move has gained a lot of popularity in recent years. The point is seen in the line  3...d5  @@StartBracket@@Black does normally want to avoid  allowing e2-e4,  although the option of  3...Bg7  4.e4  d6  , switching to a Pirc, does exist.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/5np1/3p4/3P4/5N2/PPPNPPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  Bg7  5.b4!?  ,  where White will be going for a plan of gaining space on the queenside, heavily discouraging the ...c5 counterplay, and planning to go for c4 later on.  We have a lot of possible options in response, and the one I am proposing has the advantage of putting White's plan under immediate pressure. It can also lead to some very wild complications, which I tend to favor whenever possible in the barrens of the Anti-Grünfeld. }
3... c5
{ As a safer backup plan, I would suggest something along the lines of  3...d5  4.e3  a5!?  I really don't like allowing the b4 space-grab.  5.c4  Bg7  6.b3  O-O  7.Bb2  e6!?  8.Be2  b6  9.O-O  Bb7  ,  aiming to finish development with ...Nbd7, ...Qe7, and then start looking for ...c5. }
4. dxc5 { This is what most people chose so far in this spot. } 4... Qa5 5. a3
Qxc5 6. b4 Qc7 7. Bb2 Bg7
{ We are getting a very decent double-fianchetto hedgehog. } 8. c4 O-O 9. e3 b6
10. Be2 Bb7 11. O-O d6
{ We're likely to get to this position, by some move order or other, since both sides are making the moves they can't do without. }
12. Rc1
{ 12.Nd4  Nbd7  13.Bf3  Ne5  14.Bxb7  Qxb7  as in Kotsur-Grischuk, Astana 2012, is also totally fine. }
12... Nbd7
{ Our plan is to play ...Rac8 and ...Qb8, and then react to whatever White is doing. Sometimes doubling on the c-file with ...Rc7 and ...Rfc8 is sensible, the queen is often quite well placed on a8, and very importantly, White doesn't have particularly clear-cut plans either. The two games underneath illustrate how play might continue.   13.Qb3  Rac8  14.Rfd1  Qb8  15.Bf1  Rfd8  16.Nd4  Qa8  17.Ba1  a6  1/2-1/2 Bukavshin-Gelfand, Moscow 2015.   13.Nb1  Rac8  14.Nc3  Qb8  15.Qb3  Qa8  16.Rfd1  a6  17.Na4  Bc6  18.Nc3  Bb7  19.h3  Rc7  20.Ne1  Rfc8  21.Rc2  Bh8  22.Kh2  Bg7  23.Kg1  1/2-1/2 Fedoseev-Grischuk, Baku 2015. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. 2. Nf3 g6 3.Nbd2"]
[Black "3.Nbd2 c5 4.e3 − 4.e4 | Informational 5...Nh5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Nbd2
{ This seemingly innocuous move has gained a lot of popularity in recent years. The point is seen in the line  3...d5  @@StartBracket@@Black does normally want to avoid  allowing e2-e4,  although the option of  3...Bg7  4.e4  d6  , switching to a Pirc, does exist.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/5np1/3p4/3P4/5N2/PPPNPPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  Bg7  5.b4!?  ,  where White will be going for a plan of gaining space on the queenside, heavily discouraging the ...c5 counterplay, and planning to go for c4 later on.  We have a lot of possible options in response, and the one I am proposing has the advantage of putting White's plan under immediate pressure. It can also lead to some very wild complications, which I tend to favor whenever possible in the barrens of the Anti-Grünfeld. }
3... c5
{ As a safer backup plan, I would suggest something along the lines of  3...d5  4.e3  a5!?  I really don't like allowing the b4 space-grab.  5.c4  Bg7  6.b3  O-O  7.Bb2  e6!?  8.Be2  b6  9.O-O  Bb7  ,  aiming to finish development with ...Nbd7, ...Qe7, and then start looking for ...c5. }
4. e4
{ A very rare move already, but the only one, I believe, that has any shot of offering White any edge. In practice, White overwhelmingly chooses either  4.dxc5  or  4.e3  .   4.c3  cxd4  5.cxd4  is yet another instance of a very bad runout for White. After  5...d5!  ,  followed by ...Nc6, the difference in the Nd2 and ...Nc6 development makes Black very happy. }
4... cxd4 5. e5 Nh5
{ My wonderful editor, Alina, attracted my attention to the possibility of playing 5...Nh5 here, and indeed, it's quite a viable alternative that requires White to play very energetically, and in most cases sacrifice at least the pawn on e5 for the initiative. }
6. Nxd4 Qa5 7. Be2 Nc6 { 7...Qxe5?  8.Nc4  is bad. } 8. c3 Qxe5 9. Nc4 Qd5 10.
O-O
{ In the end, such lines seemed unnecessary to me. Plus the positions you will see in the main line of the 5...Nd5 are too fun to miss out on. }
*

