1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Nbd2
{ This seemingly innocuous move has gained a lot of popularity in recent years. The point is seen in the line  3...d5  @@StartBracket@@Black does normally want to avoid  allowing e2-e4,  although the option of  3...Bg7  4.e4  d6  , switching to a Pirc, does exist.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/5np1/3p4/3P4/5N2/PPPNPPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  Bg7  5.b4!?  ,  where White will be going for a plan of gaining space on the queenside, heavily discouraging the ...c5 counterplay, and planning to go for c4 later on.  We have a lot of possible options in response, and the one I am proposing has the advantage of putting White's plan under immediate pressure. It can also lead to some very wild complications, which I tend to favor whenever possible in the barrens of the Anti-Grünfeld. }
3... c5
{ As a safer backup plan, I would suggest something along the lines of  3...d5  4.e3  a5!?  I really don't like allowing the b4 space-grab.  5.c4  Bg7  6.b3  O-O  7.Bb2  e6!?  8.Be2  b6  9.O-O  Bb7  ,  aiming to finish development with ...Nbd7, ...Qe7, and then start looking for ...c5. }
4. e4
{ A very rare move already, but the only one, I believe, that has any shot of offering White any edge. In practice, White overwhelmingly chooses either  4.dxc5  or  4.e3  .   4.c3  cxd4  5.cxd4  is yet another instance of a very bad runout for White. After  5...d5!  ,  followed by ...Nc6, the difference in the Nd2 and ...Nc6 development makes Black very happy. }
4... cxd4 5. e5 Nd5 6. Bc4
{ This move is almost a novelty, with very very few games in my database − but it's by far the best in the position. }
6... Nb6 7. Bb3
{ Now we have to be extremely careful since White's play against the f7-pawn @@StartBracket@@and the archetypical for the 2020s plans of h4-h5 once we castle@@EndBracket@@ are very dangerous. }
7... Bg7
{ More precise than  7...Nc6  8.Ng5  since being able to castle at will is much more important  than protecting d4 here. }
8. a4 d5
{ Freeing up the d7-square in case of a5. We shouldn't just autopilot  8...a5  which weakens our Nb6 for the future. Instead, we should progress with our own game plan. }
9. exd6
{ 9.a5?  N6d7  followed  by ...Nc6, with the idea of pressuring the e5-pawn. }
9... Qxd6 10. a5 N6d7 11. Ne4 Qc7 12. c3 O-O
{ There's no need for us to get involved with  12...dxc3  13.Bxf7+!? } 13. Nxd4
Nc6
{ We're completely fine. Black threatens to saddle the opponent with an isolated pawn on d4, while  14.Nxc6  bxc6!?  prepares ...Ba6 and opens the b-file for the a8-rook. }
