[Black "3.Nbd2 c5 4.e3 − 6.Bc4 #6 | Informational 10...Nxe5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Nbd2
{ This seemingly innocuous move has gained a lot of popularity in recent years. The point is seen in the line  3...d5  @@StartBracket@@Black does normally want to avoid  allowing e2-e4,  although the option of  3...Bg7  4.e4  d6  , switching to a Pirc, does exist.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/5np1/3p4/3P4/5N2/PPPNPPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  Bg7  5.b4!?  ,  where White will be going for a plan of gaining space on the queenside, heavily discouraging the ...c5 counterplay, and planning to go for c4 later on.  We have a lot of possible options in response, and the one I am proposing has the advantage of putting White's plan under immediate pressure. It can also lead to some very wild complications, which I tend to favor whenever possible in the barrens of the Anti-Grünfeld. }
3... c5
{ As a safer backup plan, I would suggest something along the lines of  3...d5  4.e3  a5!?  I really don't like allowing the b4 space-grab.  5.c4  Bg7  6.b3  O-O  7.Bb2  e6!?  8.Be2  b6  9.O-O  Bb7  ,  aiming to finish development with ...Nbd7, ...Qe7, and then start looking for ...c5. }
4. e4
{ A very rare move already, but the only one, I believe, that has any shot of offering White any edge. In practice, White overwhelmingly chooses either  4.dxc5  or  4.e3  .   4.c3  cxd4  5.cxd4  is yet another instance of a very bad runout for White. After  5...d5!  ,  followed by ...Nc6, the difference in the Nd2 and ...Nc6 development makes Black very happy. }
4... cxd4 5. e5 Nd5 6. Bc4
{ Almost a novelty, with very very few games in my database − but it's by far the best here. }
6... Nb6 7. Bb3
{ We have to be extremely careful since White's play against the f7-pawn @@StartBracket@@and the archetypical for the 2020s plans of h4-h5 once we castle@@EndBracket@@ are very dangerous. }
7... Bg7
{ More precise than  7...Nc6  8.Ng5  since being able to castle at will is much more important  than protecting d4 here. }
8. Ne4 { 8.Ng5?  d5  9.exd6  O-O!  is precisely why we played 7...Bg7. } 8...
Nc6 9. Bg5 O-O { We can't allow Nd6+, of course. } 10. h4 Nxe5
{ It pains me a little bit to offer  10...h6!?  instead of  10...Nxe5  , because there is a very specific position here down the line which I wanted to share with you. But 10...h6 is easier to understand and leaves White with fewer options along the way. }
11. Nxe5
{ 11.Nd6  runs into an extremely beautiful riposte:  11...Na4!  The knight is taboo in view of ...Qa5+, while both ...Nxb2 and ...Nc5 are on the agenda.  12.Nxe5   12.O-O  Nc5!  Once the Bb3 gets traded off, and we have access to f6, White's attack falters completely.  12...Qa5+  , and now the more or less forced sequence:  13.Kf1  Bxe5  14.Bxe7  Bxd6  15.Bxd6  Qa6+  16.Kg1  Qxd6  17.Bxa4  leads to a position where Black is fine after both  17...Qf6  followed by ...d6,  or  17...b6  and ...Bb7. }
11... Bxe5 12. f4 d5
{ This is a choice −  12...Bg7  13.Nd6!  h6  also holds, as far as I could tell, but there is a specific position a bit later down the road that I wanted to showcase. }
13. fxe5 dxe4
{ A very unusual-looking central setup − Black's pawns appear to have snuck past White's barricades, but the main action will be on the kingside, where White is trying to open up the h-file and give mate. The first objective is definitely achievable, but we should be able to avoid the 2nd if we're careful. }
14. h5
{ 14.Bh6  a5!  The threat of ...a5-a4 is extremely annoying, and softening up the Bb3 if White chooses to play a4 in reply is quite important.  15.a4   15.Bxf8  Kxf8  16.O-O  @@StartBracket@@After  16.a4  d3  , we transpose to the 15.a4 variation.@@EndBracket@@  And now we have to throw more wood onto the pyre:  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1k2/1p2pp1p/1n4p1/p3P3/3pp2P/1B6/PPP3P1/R2Q1RK1 b - - 1 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Bf5!  17.g4  e6!  18.gxf5  Qxh4!  Despite being a rook down, our combined threat of a perpetual on the g3-h3 squares, and the immense pawn center we will get if we take on f5, ensure we're not worse at all.  15...d3!  16.Bxf8   16.cxd3  exd3  17.Bxf8  Kxf8  18.Qf3  Bf5  19.g4  Qd4!  This is why we included ...a5 and a4, so that after  20.gxf5  Qb4+  ,  the bishop is undefended on b3.  16...Kxf8  17.h5  Qd4!  , and our counterplay is in time:  18.hxg6  Qe3+  19.Kf1  Qf4+  20.Kg1  Qe3+=  . }
14... Bf5
{ We can't afford to let White open the h-file entirely yet. Provoking g4 ensures that the white queen will have to take a much longer route to the kingside. }
15. g4 Be6 16. Qe2
{ 16.hxg6  Nc4!  gives us a lot of immediate counterplay − ...Qa5 is now a threat, and we can generally allow gxh7 since that pawn will work as a makeshift shield for our king, e.g.  17.Bxc4  Bxc4  18.gxh7+  Kh8  19.c3  Qd7  , with a very unclear position. }
16... Nd7
{ We need to generate as much counterplay as possible. White is of course intending to castle long, while Qe2-h2 is also a topic of worry. }
17. O-O-O
{ 17.Bxe6  @@StartBracket@@The greedy  17.hxg6?  Qa5!  allows us to take over.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp1npp1p/4B1p1/4P1BP/3pp1P1/8/PPP1Q3/R3K2R b KQ - 0 17@@EndFEN@@  17...fxe6  18.O-O-O  d3!  19.Qxe4  Nc5!  with ...Qd5 to follow, is good for us, while after  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp1np2p/4p1p1/4P1BP/4p1P1/3p4/PPP1Q3/2KR3R w - - 0 19@@EndFEN@@  19.cxd3  Qb6!  ,  the position is quite unclear. Note how a lot of the intrigue is centered around trying not to give White a free tempo to take on g6. }
17... Bxb3 { 17...d3?  18.Qh2!  loses on the spot. } 18. hxg6
{ Threatening Qh2 followed by mate on the h-file.   18.axb3?!  Qa5  19.Qh2??  Nxe5!  White loses since our counterplay gets there just in time. }
18... Rc8
{ Our main enemy here is the threat of Qh2, so we're playing to stop it as much as possible. }
19. axb3 d3 20. Qxe4 Nc5
{ We're not interested in taking on c2 with a rook, since ...dxc2 will almost always create a much bigger disruption. }
21. Qc4
{ 21.gxh7+  leads to an equal-ish endgame pretty much by force:  21...Kh8  22.Qf5  Nxb3+  23.Kb1  dxc2+  24.Qxc2  Rxc2  25.Rxd8  Rxd8  26.Kxc2  Nd4+=  . }
21... b5 22. Qxb5 Qa5
{ This is the position I so desperately wanted to show the viewers :@@EndBracket@@ I find this tactical shot very much worthy of dedicating a whole chapter to. It also has the advantage of being correct.   A sample line to illustrate the accuracy of Black's move and how play might continue is  23.Qc4   23.gxh7+?!  Kg7  is actually a bit better for us:  24.Qc4  dxc2  25.Rdf1  Nd3+!  26.Qxd3  Qa1+  27.Kd2  c1=Q+  28.Rxc1  Qxb2+  29.Ke1  Rxc1+  30.Bxc1  Qxc1+  31.Qd1  Qf4  and our king is, if anything, safer than its counterpart, while our active queen creates a lot of issues.  23...hxg6  ,  it is finally safe to take on g6 now − we have enough play on the other side of the board not to worry about the h-file too much anymore.  24.Rh6   24.Bxe7  Ne4  25.Qxe4  dxc2  26.Rde1  Qa1+  27.Kd2  c1=Q+  28.Rxc1  Qxb2+  29.Rc2  Rxc2+  30.Qxc2  Qd4+  31.Qd3  Qb2+=  .  24...dxc2  25.Rxg6+  Kh7  26.Rh6+  Kg8  27.Rg6+  Kh7=  with a perpetual. Of course @@StartFEN@@2r2r2/p3pp1k/7R/q1n1P1B1/2Q3P1/1P6/1Pp5/2KR4 b - - 2 26@@EndFEN@@  26...Kg7?  instead, would be a terrible blunder as after  27.Bf6+  exf6  28.exf6+  Kxh6  29.Qf4+  , mate can't be prevented. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. 2. Nf3 g6 3.Nbd2"]
[Black "3.Nbd2 c5 4.e3 − 6.Bc4 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Nbd2
{ This seemingly innocuous move has gained a lot of popularity in recent years. The point is seen in the line  3...d5  @@StartBracket@@Black does normally want to avoid  allowing e2-e4,  although the option of  3...Bg7  4.e4  d6  , switching to a Pirc, does exist.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/5np1/3p4/3P4/5N2/PPPNPPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  Bg7  5.b4!?  ,  where White will be going for a plan of gaining space on the queenside, heavily discouraging the ...c5 counterplay, and planning to go for c4 later on.  We have a lot of possible options in response, and the one I am proposing has the advantage of putting White's plan under immediate pressure. It can also lead to some very wild complications, which I tend to favor whenever possible in the barrens of the Anti-Grünfeld. }
3... c5
{ As a safer backup plan, I would suggest something along the lines of  3...d5  4.e3  a5!?  I really don't like allowing the b4 space-grab.  5.c4  Bg7  6.b3  O-O  7.Bb2  e6!?  8.Be2  b6  9.O-O  Bb7  ,  aiming to finish development with ...Nbd7, ...Qe7, and then start looking for ...c5. }
4. e4
{ A very rare move already, but the only one, I believe, that has any shot of offering White any edge. In practice, White overwhelmingly chooses either  4.dxc5  or  4.e3  .   4.c3  cxd4  5.cxd4  is yet another instance of a very bad runout for White. After  5...d5!  ,  followed by ...Nc6, the difference in the Nd2 and ...Nc6 development makes Black very happy. }
4... cxd4 5. e5 Nd5 6. Bc4
{ This move is almost a novelty, with very very few games in my database − but it's by far the best in the position. }
6... Nb6 7. Bb3
{ Now we have to be extremely careful since White's play against the f7-pawn @@StartBracket@@and the archetypical for the 2020s plans of h4-h5 once we castle@@EndBracket@@ are very dangerous. }
7... Bg7
{ More precise than  7...Nc6  8.Ng5  since being able to castle at will is much more important  than protecting d4 here. }
8. Ne4 { 8.Ng5?  d5  9.exd6  O-O!  is precisely why we played 7...Bg7. } 8...
Nc6 9. Bg5 O-O { We can't allow Nd6+, of course. } 10. h4 h6
{ We don't need to remove the e5-pawn to free up our own play. And if I'm honest, the final position of the line is crazy enough to make me forgive this move for usurping the place of  10...Nxe5  . }
11. Bf4 d5 12. exd6 Bf5
{ White is just completely busted since a full retreat is required in the center. }
*

