{ This seemingly innocuous move has gained a lot of popularity in recent years. The point is seen in the line  3...d5  @@StartBracket@@Black does normally want to avoid  allowing e2-e4,  although the option of  3...Bg7  4.e4  d6  , switching to a Pirc, does exist.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/5np1/3p4/3P4/5N2/PPPNPPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  Bg7  5.b4!?  ,  where White will be going for a plan of gaining space on the queenside, heavily discouraging the ...c5 counterplay, and planning to go for c4 later on.  We have a lot of possible options in response, and the one I am proposing has the advantage of putting White's plan under immediate pressure. It can also lead to some very wild complications, which I tend to favor whenever possible in the barrens of the Anti-Grünfeld. }
3... c5
{ As a safer backup plan, I would suggest something along the lines of  3...d5  4.e3  a5!?  I really don't like allowing the b4 space-grab.  5.c4  Bg7  6.b3  O-O  7.Bb2  e6!?  8.Be2  b6  9.O-O  Bb7  ,  aiming to finish development with ...Nbd7, ...Qe7, and then start looking for ...c5. }
4. e4
{ A very rare move already, but the only one, I believe, that has any shot of offering White any edge. In practice, White overwhelmingly chooses either  4.dxc5  or  4.e3  .   4.c3  cxd4  5.cxd4  is yet another instance of a very bad runout for White. After  5...d5!  ,  followed by ...Nc6, the difference in the Nd2 and ...Nc6 development makes Black very happy. }
4... cxd4 5. e5 Nd5 6. Bc4
{ This move is almost a novelty, with very very few games in my database − but it's by far the best in the position. }
6... Nb6 7. Bb3
{ Now we have to be extremely careful since White's play against the f7-pawn @@StartBracket@@and the archetypical for the 2020s plans of h4-h5 once we castle@@EndBracket@@ are very dangerous. }
7... Bg7
{ More precise than  7...Nc6  8.Ng5  since being able to castle at will is much more important  than protecting d4 here. }
8. Ne4 { 8.Ng5?  d5  9.exd6  O-O!  is precisely why we played 7...Bg7. } 8...
Nc6 9. Bg5 O-O { We can't allow Nd6+, of course. } 10. h4 h6
{ We don't need to remove the e5-pawn to free up our own play. And if I'm honest, the final position of the line is crazy enough to make me forgive this move for usurping the place of  10...Nxe5  . }
11. h5 { Absolutely the only way to continue. } 11... hxg5 12. hxg6 e6
{ Of course, the Bb3 needs to be neutralized asap. } 13. gxf7+
{ Once again, the only way to continue the attack. In fact, White's next few moves are all but forced. }
13... Rxf7 14. Nfxg5 Nxe5 15. Qh5 d5
{ Further restricting the Bb3, and starting to include the Q-side in the game. Plus, of course, attacking the Ne4. }
16. f4 Rxf4
{ Our knight is extremely important in the defense of the king, we can't allow White to take it. }
17. O-O-O dxe4 { That's why we played d5! } 18. Bxe6+ Kf8
{ 18...Bxe6?  19.Qh7+  Kf8  20.Nxe6+  wouldn't be very good. } 19. Nh7+ Ke7 20.
Qg5+ Kxe6 { 20...Ke8?  21.Qxg7  Bxe6  22.Qxe5  is bad. } 21. Qxd8 Bd7
{ I left White's moves uncommented upon in this entire sequence since they had no reasonable alternatives at any point. And now we got here, let's take stock. We have three pieces for the queen − a material @@StartBracket@@im@@EndBracket@@balance I quite like on the side of the pieces, quite often.   Our king is in the center, but it has a very decent cover − the e4/d4-pawns are very useful, and the pieces are also suddenly very well coordinated. If White fails to make much progress here, we will definitely be in the ascendance. Play could continue  22.Ng5+   22.Qg5?!  Rg4  23.Rh6+  Bxh6  24.Qxh6+  Rg6  doesn't work out.  22...Kd5  23.Qc7  Rc8  24.Qxb7+  Rc6  25.Qxa7  e3  and this is obviously a mess, but it's a mess where if I couldn't see the dreaded 0.00 after the cold-blooded  26.Kb1!!  , I would think Black must be better. Our king, despite being very centralized, is completely safe, and we simply have more pieces on the board to play  with @@StartBracket@@...Rf2 and ...Bf5 are also legitimate ideas, with pressure on the c2-pawn@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. Colle System 2.Nf3 g6 3.e3"]
[Black "Colle 4.Bd3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3
{ 2.e3  g6  is going to be roughly the same −  White can’t really play the Colle without Nf3 unless they want to suddenly switch to playing the Stonewall, which doesn’t scare us either. }
2... g6 3. e3
{ You can make an argument that being locked into the fianchetto systems is a bit of a drawback vs. the London. It is, however, an upgrade against the Colle − and I say that as someone who's played a LOT of Colle in my youth. By not even providing White with an easily understood plan of pushing e3-e4 after the opening, we will achieve very comfortable positions by almost any logical means. }
3... Bg7 4. Bd3 { This move is a much worse version of the  4.Be2  line. } 4...
O-O 5. c4
{ White's setup can be met in a number of ways, but the most straightforward is the text move. }
5... c5
{ Our plan, if White ignores this, is to play ...cxd4 followed by ...d5, with a very good setup. }
6. dxc5 Na6 7. Nc3 Nxc5 8. O-O b6 { The current position is very nice for us. }
*

