{ Instead of  12...d6  as in Malakhov-Grischuk, Novi Sad 2016, which allowed White to play  13.Nd5  , with approximate equality, I prefer to begin with the text move. }
13. Rad1 d6
{ Pinning the knight to c3 by pressuring the c2-pawn. This is a very comfortable Sicilian with our two bishops. The double a-pawns are largely irrelevant, and in fact, you can also play @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pbqpppbp/p4np1/8/4P3/2NQBN2/PPP2PPP/R3R1K1 b - - 3 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Rfc8  ,  aiming to put the other rook on b8 later, and using both the semi-open files to our advantage. }
