[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5
{ The Trompowsky has been somewhat surpassed in recent years by its more restrained @@StartBracket@@or, shall we say, 'boring'?@@EndBracket@@ brother the London − but it's still an occasional visitor even at the very top level. And here  (an important deviation from my approach to the London for this series)  , I will not commit to playing ...g6 anyway since the Tromp players don't have the option of forcing us to do it by starting with Nf3 first. }
2... d5
{ In my own games, I have always played  2...Ne4  , but that's mainly due to inertia and laziness. The text move is much more sensible. }
3. Nf3
{ Probably the easiest move to deal with, for us, in this position.  3.Nc3  would transpose to theVeresov chapter. }
3... Ne4
{ The inclusion of ...d5 and Nf3 makes playing this move much more comfortable for us since it can't easily be chased away by f2-f3. }
4. Bf4 c5 5. e3 { And now I quite like a little queen dance: } 5... Qb6 6. Nc3
{ 6.Qc1  Nc6  clearly doesn't concern us. } 6... Qa5 7. Bb5+ Nc6 8. O-O Nxc3
{ Time to force some pieces off the board. } 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. bxc3 g6
{ A very strange position arises. White is currently ahead in development, but we have the bishop pair and a sturdy pawn structure. In two moves, our king will be safely castled, and then there will be little to worry about. }
11. Re1
{ 11.Ne5?  f6  is not great for White since the  pawn on c6 can't be taken without the knight getting corralled. }
11... Bg7 12. e4 dxe4 13. Rxe4
{ We don't need to obsess about the e7-pawn − we have play vs. the white Q-side. Therefore, gaining a tempo prevails. }
13... Bf5 14. Re3 O-O { We have a very decent game in this position. } *

