1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5
{ The Trompowsky has been somewhat surpassed in recent years by its more restrained @@StartBracket@@or, shall we say, 'boring'?@@EndBracket@@ brother the London − but it's still an occasional visitor even at the very top level. And here  (an important deviation from my approach to the London for this series)  , I will not commit to playing ...g6 anyway since the Tromp players don't have the option of forcing us to do it by starting with Nf3 first. }
2... d5
{ In my own games, I have always played  2...Ne4  , but that's mainly due to inertia and laziness. The text move is much more sensible. }
3. Nd2 { 3.Nc3  would transpose to theVeresov chapter. } 3... c5 4. dxc5 e6 5.
e4 h6
{ There's an absolutely mad line starting with  5...Bxc5  6.e5  Qb6  which would be fun to suggest since I believe it works, but the text move is a more sensible solution. }
6. Bh4 Be7
{ There's nothing wrong with the simple  6...dxe4  7.Nxe4  Qa5+  8.Nd2  Qxc5  ,  as was played by Aronian vs. Karjakin in 2020 − but this is sharper and more ambitious, I believe. We're maintaining the pressure in the center while finishing development, and letting White decide what to do with the hanging e4 and c5-pawns. }
7. Ngf3 dxe4 8. Bxf6 Bxf6 9. Nxe4 Qxd1+
{ Obviously, being able to take on b2 next, this is an endgame we are not fearing. }
10. Rxd1 Bxb2 11. Bb5+ Ke7
{ Black is doing fine with the flawless pawn structure and the bishop pair. } *

