{ The Trompowsky has been somewhat surpassed in recent years by its more restrained @@StartBracket@@or, shall we say, 'boring'?@@EndBracket@@ brother the London − but it's still an occasional visitor even at the very top level. And here  (an important deviation from my approach to the London for this series)  , I will not commit to playing ...g6 anyway since the Tromp players don't have the option of forcing us to do it by starting with Nf3 first. }
2... d5
{ In my own games, I have always played  2...Ne4  , but that's mainly due to inertia and laziness. The text move is much more sensible. }
3. Nd2 { 3.Nc3  would transpose to theVeresov chapter. } 3... c5 4. e3 cxd4
{ We're going for the tempo play here since White's setup is very sturdy, and will start making decent sense if we allow c3, Bd3, and then perhaps even f4 followed by Ngf3. }
5. exd4 Qb6
{ We're not hoping to actually win material, of course, but luring the knight to b3 is a win in itself. }
6. Ngf3 Nc6 7. Nb3 Bf5
{ It is very important to get this bishop outside the pawn chain before we play ...e6. Our plan is to play ...e6, and then perhaps ...Bd6 if allowed, with ...Ne4 often thrown in. The 'if allowed' in the previous sentence is not accidental. As you will see, White will often spend a tempo on returning the bishop from g5 to f4, both to prevent us from occupying that diagonal ourselves with ...Bd6, and to preempt our ...Ne4. }
8. c3 e6 9. Bf4 Be7
{ 9...Nh5!?  10.Be3  Be7  , driving the bishop  away from f4, and intending to finish development, drop the queen back to c7 to prevent its return, and then bring the knight back, is also very sensible. }
10. Be2 a5 11. a4 Ne4 12. O-O O-O
{ Black was completely fine in Artemiev-Jakovenko, Poikovsky 2019 − we're planning to play ...Bd6, neutralizing the one really good piece White has, and our solid pawn structure ensures our safety. }
*

