[Black "Trompowsky Attack 4.e3 c5 5.c3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5
{ The Trompowsky has been somewhat surpassed in recent years by its more restrained @@StartBracket@@or, shall we say, 'boring'?@@EndBracket@@ brother the London − but it's still an occasional visitor even at the very top level. And here  (an important deviation from my approach to the London for this series)  , I will not commit to playing ...g6 anyway since the Tromp players don't have the option of forcing us to do it by starting with Nf3 first. }
2... d5
{ In my own games, I have always played  2...Ne4  , but that's mainly due to inertia and laziness. The text move is much more sensible. }
3. Bxf6 gxf6
{ 3...exf6  is safer  and entirely playable too. We'll be developing the bishop to d6, castle K-side, and when White plays c4, we'll trade and aim to finish development by playing ...f5 and ...Nd7-f6.    3...gxf6  is more concrete.  We're playing ...c5 next move, almost no matter what, and then aiming to go for very fast development in the center with ...Nc6 and ...e5. The doubling of the f-pawns is somewhat annoying, but it also gives us additional firepower by further supporting that ...e5 push. }
4. e3 c5 5. c3 { Too passive. } 5... e5
{ Our center exerts a lot of pressure. } 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Nbd2 cxd4 8. cxd4 Bd6
{ This is a rare position where we might castle kingside − but more importantly, we're in a very dominant position in the center, allowing us a lot of flexibility with future plans. }
9. Bb5 O-O 10. O-O e4 11. Nh4 Kh8
{ Our plan of brute-forcing an attack on the K-side is a lot less simple to deal with than one might suspect. }
