{ 3...exf6  is safer  and entirely playable too. We'll be developing the bishop to d6, castle K-side, and when White plays c4, we'll trade and aim to finish development by playing ...f5 and ...Nd7-f6.    3...gxf6  is more concrete.  We're playing ...c5 next move, almost no matter what, and then aiming to go for very fast development in the center with ...Nc6 and ...e5. The doubling of the f-pawns is somewhat annoying, but it also gives us additional firepower by further supporting that ...e5 push. }
4. e3 c5 5. dxc5 Nc6
{ I prefer this to  5...e6  which is also fine,  but in my opinion, somewhat less forcing, and definitely gives us less chance for a double-edged position. }
6. Bb5 e6 7. c4 { This plan is much safer, but we're completely fine. } 7...
dxc4 8. Nd2 { And now I prefer a somewhat rarer reply. } 8... Qd5 9. Ngf3 Qxc5
10. Bxc4 Bg7
{ We're fine − we'll castle, play ...Qe7 @@StartBracket@@or even ...Qb4@@EndBracket@@, ...Bd7, ...Rac8 and ...f5. }
11. O-O O-O 12. Rc1 Qb4 13. b3 Rd8
{ Black is not at all worse given the piece activity and pair of bishops. It more than compensates for the slightly damaged structure on the K-side. Typical for these types of positions is to finish development with ...Bd7-e8 and ...Rac8. }
