[White "26. Trompowsky Attack 2.Bg5 d5 3.Bxf6"]
[Black "Trompowsky Attack 4.e3 c5 5.dxc5 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5
{ The Trompowsky has been somewhat surpassed in recent years by its more restrained @@StartBracket@@or, shall we say, 'boring'?@@EndBracket@@ brother the London − but it's still an occasional visitor even at the very top level. And here  (an important deviation from my approach to the London for this series)  , I will not commit to playing ...g6 anyway since the Tromp players don't have the option of forcing us to do it by starting with Nf3 first. }
2... d5
{ In my own games, I have always played  2...Ne4  , but that's mainly due to inertia and laziness. The text move is much more sensible. }
3. Bxf6 gxf6
{ 3...exf6  is safer  and entirely playable too. We'll be developing the bishop to d6, castle K-side, and when White plays c4, we'll trade and aim to finish development by playing ...f5 and ...Nd7-f6.    3...gxf6  is more concrete.  We're playing ...c5 next move, almost no matter what, and then aiming to go for very fast development in the center with ...Nc6 and ...e5. The doubling of the f-pawns is somewhat annoying, but it also gives us additional firepower by further supporting that ...e5 push. }
4. e3 c5 5. dxc5 Nc6
{ I prefer this to  5...e6  which is also fine,  but in my opinion, somewhat less forcing, and definitely gives us less chance for a double-edged position. }
6. Bb5 e6 7. b4
{ The way to go for a sharp unclear position, but I don't think we're unhappy about it. }
7... a5 8. c3
{ We won't be able to win the pawn back, but the amount of effort it will cost White to keep this setup stable will provide us with a lot of counterplay. }
8... Bd7 { A safer option than  8...Bg7  , which is addressed later on. } 9.
Qb3 { The only way to preserve the Q-side. } 9... Ne5
{ Forcing the bishop trade, and preparing to further undermine the Q-side with ...b6. There is also some hint of ...Nd3+ ideas after the bishops come off. }
10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 11. Nf3
{ The only sensible move − White needs to develop, and the Ne5 has to be challenged. }
11... axb4 12. cxb4 Qa4
{ We take the most concrete approach to the position by capturing on b4 first, before offering this queen trade. White is given no time to stabilize the position. }
13. Qxa4+ Rxa4 14. a3 b6
{ Hitting the nail on the head and very much in line with the note on move 12 − we have to act fast. }
15. Nc3 Ra8
{ This position will eithertranspose to 12.Nxe5, or lead to equality after, for instance,  16.Nb5  Kd7  17.cxb6  Bxb4+  18.Ke2  Ba5  . }
