[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5
{ The Trompowsky has been somewhat surpassed in recent years by its more restrained @@StartBracket@@or, shall we say, 'boring'?@@EndBracket@@ brother the London − but it's still an occasional visitor even at the very top level. And here  (an important deviation from my approach to the London for this series)  , I will not commit to playing ...g6 anyway since the Tromp players don't have the option of forcing us to do it by starting with Nf3 first. }
2... d5
{ In my own games, I have always played  2...Ne4  , but that's mainly due to inertia and laziness. The text move is much more sensible. }
3. Bxf6 gxf6
{ 3...exf6  is safer  and entirely playable too. We'll be developing the bishop to d6, castle K-side, and when White plays c4, we'll trade and aim to finish development by playing ...f5 and ...Nd7-f6.    3...gxf6  is more concrete.  We're playing ...c5 next move, almost no matter what, and then aiming to go for very fast development in the center with ...Nc6 and ...e5. The doubling of the f-pawns is somewhat annoying, but it also gives us additional firepower by further supporting that ...e5 push. }
4. e3 c5 5. dxc5 Nc6
{ I prefer this to  5...e6  which is also fine,  but in my opinion, somewhat less forcing, and definitely gives us less chance for a double-edged position. }
6. Bb5 e6 7. b4
{ The way to go for a sharp unclear position, but I don't think we're unhappy about it. }
7... a5 8. c3
{ For those of you looking for a very messy and unbalanced positions to play, I would recommend }
8... Bg7 { here. } 9. Ne2 O-O
{ I like this better than  9...f5  −  by unpinning the Nc6, we're forcing White to spend a tempo on a3 instead of  10.Nd4  ,  which would have been the reply in case of 9...f5. }
10. a3 f5
{ Or the immediate  10...axb4  11.Bxc6  bxc6  12.cxb4  f5  13.Ra2  e5  14.O-O  Re8  . }
11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Ra2 e5 13. O-O Re8
{ We have a very curious position on our hands. White is a pawn up, but Black's fantastic center and active pieces provide us with tremendous compensation. The c8-bishop will be very strong on a6, while we can also go for a direct attack on the K-side with ...Re6-h6 if White is too slow.  One thing to make note of is that we must try to prevent White from ever getting a foothold for the knights. In particular, playing ...e5-e4 and giving Ne2 a fantastic outpost on d4 would be a mistake, and in fact, you will often see the engine here play ...f5-f4 first, provoking exf4, and only then playing ...e5-e4, when the d4-square is no longer supported by the pawn on e3. }
14. Nd2 { White's continuation allows us to advance in the center. } 14... d4
{ Opening up the position to maximize the strength of our bishop pair. } 15.
exd4 exd4 16. Nxd4 Bxd4 17. cxd4 axb4 18. Nc4 Be6
{ Given the various pins, White has to be careful already. } *

