[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27. 1.g3 Introduction"]
[Black "1.g3 d5 2.Bg2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. g3 d5
{ The most consistent way of playing against 1.g3. We're immediately beginning the fight for the center.  1...e5  would also be quite logical if not for the fact that  2.c4  , pivoting into the English, exists. }
2. Bg2 e5
{ Now that White can't force us to play the English, we're quite happy to play ...e5. }
3. c4 d4 4. d3 a5
{ We're making this move early so that we won't forget to make it later.  4...Nc6  is also playable, and should lead to the same, just remember to play ...a5 in time.  5.Nf3  Nf6  6.O-O  a5!  Just not  6...Be7?  7.b4  , which was suddenly very good for White in Morozevich-Karjakin, 2012. The problem is that  7...Bxb4  now runs into  8.Nxe5!  Nxe5  9.Qa4+  winning back the piece with the better game. }
5. Nf3 Nc6 6. O-O Nf6
{ This is a very nice Réti for us since White is too slow. } 7. Na3 Bc5 8. Nb5
{ An empty gesture. } 8... O-O 9. Bg5 Be7 10. e3 h6
{ We were following Topalov-Giri, Leuven 2016, but here, instead of  10...dxe3  , Black should have played the text move. }
11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. exd4 exd4
{ Eventually, we'll move our Nc6 somewhere, push the Nb5 back with ...c6, and stand very well. }
*

