1. g3 d5
{ The most consistent way of playing against 1.g3. We're immediately beginning the fight for the center.  1...e5  would also be quite logical if not for the fact that  2.c4  , pivoting into the English, exists. }
2. Bg2 e5
{ Now that White can't force us to play the English, we're quite happy to play ...e5. }
3. d3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Bd6
{ The easiest  − we're playing the Nf3/Bd3 system vs. the Pirc, and it's solid enough for the engines to suggest we're a bit better already @@StartBracket@@with Black! by move 4!@@EndBracket@@. }
5. O-O O-O 6. Nc3 { Once again, there's a wide choice of good options. } 6...
Re8
{ I like 6...Re8 the most. We're protecting e5 in case the Bd6 has to go somewhere, and we're also keeping flexible, preserving the choice between ...c5 and ...Nc6 for later. }
7. e4 d4
{ In this line, I wanted to show you an additional option and that is  7...dxe4  , which iscovered later on. }
8. Ne2 c5
{ Our plan is simple. We'll play ...Nc6 and start planning to expand on the Q-side with ...b5 and ...c4. White doesn't really have anything to look forward to apart from pushing f4, and that is just not enough of a threat. }
9. Nd2 Nc6 10. a4 a6 11. Nc4 Bc7 12. f4 Rb8
{ We can continue slowly building up on the Q-side, safe in the knowledge that our center is under no actual pressure. }
13. fxe5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Nf4 b6
{ Not giving White a chance to fix our pawn structure with a4-a5, and keeping the option for further expansion on the queenside open.   I am not that fond of  15...b5  16.axb5  as it awakens  the rook on a1. We have a very comfortable position. }
*

