{ The most consistent way of playing against 1.g3. We're immediately beginning the fight for the center.  1...e5  would also be quite logical if not for the fact that  2.c4  , pivoting into the English, exists. }
2. c4 d4
{ This will mostly transpose to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/8/6P1/PPPPPP1P/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Bg2  e5  3.c4  lines. }
3. Nf3 { 3.b4  e5  4.Bg2  transposes to the2.Bg2 move order. } 3... Nc6 4. Bg2
e5 5. O-O { 5.d3  a5  6.O-O  Nf6  is anothertransposition. } 5... e4
{ 5...Nf6  is of course also fine, but this is a very interesting and ambitious gambit idea. }
6. Ne1 h5 { We're not spending any time defending e4, our aim is the king! } 7.
d3 e3 8. fxe3 h4 { This is very dangerous for White. } 9. exd4 Nxd4 10. e3 hxg3
11. hxg3 Nf5
{ White was already in bad trouble in Gareyev-Morozevich, St. Petersburg 2018. }
*

