[Result "*"]

1. g3 d5
{ The most consistent way of playing against 1.g3. We're immediately beginning the fight for the center.  1...e5  would also be quite logical if not for the fact that  2.c4  , pivoting into the English, exists. }
2. Nf3
{ A more sensible option, once again feeding into either the g3 Grünfeld or the Tabiya. A few rare lines which lead to neither are covered here. }
2... g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. c4
{ A principled try, but we're very well equipped for it.   A@@EndBracket@@  4.d3  Nf6  5.O-O  O-O  iscovered elsewhere.   B@@EndBracket@@  4.d4  Nf6  5.O-O  O-O  see you in thenext chapter! }
4... dxc4 5. Na3 e5 6. Qc2
{ A tempo has to be spent on this move since  6.Nxc4?  e4  7.Ng1  Nf6  is extremely unpleasant due to White's lack of development. }
6... Nc6 7. Nxc4 Nge7 8. d3 O-O
{ We're very comfortable. We'd be okay anyway, but the queen on c2 gives us additional ideas, such as ...Bg4xf3 with ...Nd4 to follow. }
