{ The most consistent way of playing against 1.g3. We're immediately beginning the fight for the center.  1...e5  would also be quite logical if not for the fact that  2.c4  , pivoting into the English, exists. }
2. Nf3
{ A more sensible option, once again feeding into either the g3 Grünfeld or the Tabiya. A few rare lines which lead to neither are covered here. }
2... g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. c4
{ A principled try, but we're very well equipped for it.   A@@EndBracket@@  4.d3  Nf6  5.O-O  O-O  iscovered elsewhere.   B@@EndBracket@@  4.d4  Nf6  5.O-O  O-O  see you in thenext chapter! }
4... dxc4 5. Qa4+ Nc6 6. O-O Nh6
{ The old main line  6...e5!?  leads to a very forcing mess.  7.Nxe5!?  otherwise, we play ...Nge7 and have a very healthy setup.  7...Bxe5  8.Bxc6+  bxc6  9.Qxc6+  Bd7  10.Qe4  f6  11.f4  Bf5  12.Qe3   12.Qc6+  Bd7  13.Qe4  Bf5  is a draw.  12...Bh3!  13.Rf3  Nh6  with a very weird-looking position which the engines insist is a forced draw. But we don't need to get involved with that if we don't want to. }
7. Qxc4 Nf5 8. Nc3 O-O 9. d3 a5
{ More concrete than  9...a6  played against me by El Nino: Svidler-Anton Guijarro, chess24.com 2020.  We want to push ...a4 if White does nothing here. }
10. Qa4 Bd7 11. Qd1 Re8
{ We have a very nice game. I'd wait with ...e5 until White plays e3, so that we don't have to think how to react to Bg5 − and we definitely have enough useful moves to do that. }
12. Re1 b6
{ We have the idea of ...Rc8 next, perhaps, to get out of the long diagonal and make the c6-knight able to move, for instance, to d4. }
13. e3 e5
{ Taking a stake in the center and preventing d3-d4. Black is doing well. } *

