1. g3 d5
{ The most consistent way of playing against 1.g3. We're immediately beginning the fight for the center.  1...e5  would also be quite logical if not for the fact that  2.c4  , pivoting into the English, exists. }
2. Nf3
{ A more sensible option, once again feeding into either the g3 Grünfeld or the Tabiya. A few rare lines which lead to neither are covered here. }
2... g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O
{ A@@EndBracket@@  4.d3  Nf6  5.O-O  O-O  iscovered elsewhere.   B@@EndBracket@@  4.d4  Nf6  5.O-O  O-O  see you in thenext chapter! }
4... Nf6
{ White will have to choose between the g3 Grünfeld, the Tabiya, or 5.b3/5.d3. }
5. b3 O-O 6. Bb2
{ Now we can profitably switch to the Réti-type positions.   6.c4  d4  7.Bb2  c5  is a transposition. }
6... c5 7. c4 d4 8. b4 { 8.e3  Nc6  is very  good for us, with ...e5 to come. }
8... Re8
{ We don't need to react to b4 as long as we're preparing to play ...e5. } 9.
d3 { 9.bxc5  e5  10.d3  Na6  transposes. } 9... e5 10. bxc5
{ 10.Nbd2  cxb4  11.a3  Nc6  is not a very good Benko for White at all. } 10...
Na6 11. Nbd2 Nxc5 12. Ba3 Qc7 { We're completely fine. } 13. Ng5 h6
{ Initiating mass exchanges that will ultimately favor us. } 14. Nge4 Ncxe4 15.
Nxe4 Nxe4 16. Bxe4 Rb8 17. Rb1 b6
{ Once we trade away the Be4, we can go back to preparing ...e5-e4 with good counterplay. }
