13. Qb4 { This is not a problem. } 13... axb3 14. axb3 Rxa1 15. Rxa1 dxc4 16.
bxc4 Bxd4 { Black was at least fine in Artemiev-Dubov, Sochi 2018. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27. 1.g3 Introduction"]
[Black "1.g3 d5 2.Nf3 − 4.O-O Nf6 5.c4 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. g3 d5
{ The most consistent way of playing against 1.g3. We're immediately beginning the fight for the center.  1...e5  would also be quite logical if not for the fact that  2.c4  , pivoting into the English, exists. }
2. Nf3
{ A more sensible option, once again feeding into either the g3 Grünfeld or the Tabiya. A few rare lines which lead to neither are covered here. }
2... g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O
{ A@@EndBracket@@  4.d3  Nf6  5.O-O  O-O  iscovered elsewhere.   B@@EndBracket@@  4.d4  Nf6  5.O-O  O-O  see you in thenext chapter! }
4... Nf6
{ White will have to choose between the g3 Grünfeld, the Tabiya, or 5.b3/5.d3. }
5. c4 c6
{ I've finally given up and we're going to have a talk about this. I've never been a huge fan of this for Black and have, in fact, played this move order with White specifically to play  6.b3  here, but one has to conquer one's phobias at some point.  6.d4  is, of course, theFianchetto Variation, covered in Part  1. }
6. b3 { The only way to profit from the pawn on d2. } 6... Ne4
{ Allowing Bb2 unchallenged is also not the end of the world, but why would we? }
7. d4 O-O
{ What we have here is the 7.b3 line of theg3 Grünfeld  (Part 1)  where we chose not to play 7...dxc4. In spirit, it will in most cases resemble the lines I've shown in the7.Nbd2 a5 variation, but with ...Ne4 thrown in. }
8. Bb2 Bf5
{ White has three main options here:  9.Nc3  and  9.e3  end up very similar, in fact, they probably transpose to each other in most cases, while  9.Nbd2  stands alone in that it's more ambitious, but also riskier. }
9. Nbd2 a5 { We're always aiming for ...a5-a4 in these lines. } 10. Nh4
{ This is the idea behind Nbd2 − White forces the trade and opens up the Bg2 to perhaps trying to push e4 later, while also making it easier to protect the pawn on c4. }
10... Nxd2 11. Qxd2 Be6
{ Of course, this position would have been much easier for us if White had the bishop on c3 instead of the Qd2 − this is what I meant when I mentioned defending c4. However, we still have plenty of counterplay. }
12. Rfc1 a4
{ Opening up the a-file for trades is always going to be a useful idea here. }
13. cxd5 cxd5 14. bxa4 { And now we might even want to finesse the recapture. }
14... Nd7
{ More or less forcing White to trade away one of the bishops to prevent ...Nb6-c4. }
15. Bc3 Nb6 16. Ba5 Qd6 17. Bxb6 Qxb6 { The position is equal. } *

