2... g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O
{ A@@EndBracket@@  4.d3  Nf6  5.O-O  O-O  iscovered elsewhere.   B@@EndBracket@@  4.d4  Nf6  5.O-O  O-O  see you in thenext chapter! }
4... Nf6
{ White will have to choose between the g3 Grünfeld, the Tabiya, or 5.b3/5.d3. }
5. c4 c6
{ I've finally given up and we're going to have a talk about this. I've never been a huge fan of this for Black and have, in fact, played this move order with White specifically to play  6.b3  here, but one has to conquer one's phobias at some point.  6.d4  is, of course, theFianchetto Variation, covered in Part  1. }
6. b3 { The only way to profit from the pawn on d2. } 6... Ne4
{ Allowing Bb2 unchallenged is also not the end of the world, but why would we? }
7. d4 O-O
{ What we have here is the 7.b3 line of theg3 Grünfeld  (Part 1)  where we chose not to play 7...dxc4. In spirit, it will in most cases resemble the lines I've shown in the7.Nbd2 a5 variation, but with ...Ne4 thrown in. }
8. Bb2 Bf5
{ White has three main options here:  9.Nc3  and  9.e3  end up very similar, in fact, they probably transpose to each other in most cases, while  9.Nbd2  stands alone in that it's more ambitious, but also riskier. }
9. e3 a5 10. Nc3 Nxc3
{ 10...Nd7  is less precise, but it serves as a good warning for what to watch out for. After  11.Qe2  Nxc3  12.Bxc3  Be4  13.cxd5!  cxd5  14.Qb5  , White was a bit better in Carlsen-Duda, chess24.com 2021.  This is White's main idea: getting the queen to b5 once we've played ...a5 is quite annoying. }
11. Bxc3 Be4 12. Qe2 a4
{ 12...e6  is quite playable but less concrete. In another installment of 'oh look, another game of mine I barely remember!' I had this position with White in a very important club game vs. Radjabov, back in the 2010 ECC. }
13. Rfc1
{ 13.Bh3  is once again met by  13...c5!  14.Ng5  Nc6  with excellent counterplay. }
13... axb3 14. axb3 Rxa1 15. Rxa1
{ And now comes an important improvement I've tried to foreshadow. } 15... Qd7
{ The point is that stopping Qb5 takes precedence over pretty much everything else, but also, that developing the knight to a6 dulls much of White's pressure on the Q-side by closing down the Ra1. We might also want to play ...c5 if White does nothing.   15...Qb6  16.b4  Nd7  17.c5  was a bit better, and then suddenly completely winning by move 20ish, in Carlsen-Nepomniachtchi, Stavanger 2021. }
16. Ne5
{ This is a good way to at least desymmetrize  (is that even a word? who knows)  the position. }
16... Bxe5 17. dxe5 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 dxc4 19. bxc4 Na6
{ We are fine here, our knight can enter the game via c5 to e6/e4. } *

