[Result "*"]

1. g3 d5
{ The most consistent way of playing against 1.g3. We're immediately beginning the fight for the center.  1...e5  would also be quite logical if not for the fact that  2.c4  , pivoting into the English, exists. }
2. Nf3
{ A more sensible option, once again feeding into either the g3 Grünfeld or the Tabiya. A few rare lines which lead to neither are covered here. }
2... g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. d4 { 4.d3  Nf6  5.O-O  O-O  iscovered elsewhere. } 4...
Nf6 5. O-O O-O
{ The Tabiya − this position can arise by a multitude of move orders, and while we're not worried about White not playing  6.c4  transposing back intoPart 1, it is of course important to have a road map for the @@StartBracket@@many, sooo many@@EndBracket@@ little moves White could try here. }
6. Nbd2
{ This would be a very serious move but luckily for us, we can use our knowledge of the Grünfeld. }
6... a5
{ A very typical idea here, and you will see me recommend this move a lot. We're very interested in gaining space on the Q-side by pushing this pawn to a4, if possible. Provoking a4 in response is also a very good outcome since the gaping hole on b4 is a heavy discouragement of any c4 plans. }
7. a4 { After  7.c4  c6  we're back inPart 1. } 7... Na6 8. Ne5 c5 9. e3 Qc7
10. c3 b6
{ The extremely closed nature of the position allows us not to worry about the slightly misplaced Na6. If need be, we can actually bring it back via b8, while White isn't really going anywhere here. }
*

