[Result "*"]

1. g3 d5
{ The most consistent way of playing against 1.g3. We're immediately beginning the fight for the center.  1...e5  would also be quite logical if not for the fact that  2.c4  , pivoting into the English, exists. }
2. Nf3
{ A more sensible option, once again feeding into either the g3 Grünfeld or the Tabiya. A few rare lines which lead to neither are covered here. }
2... g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. d4 { 4.d3  Nf6  5.O-O  O-O  iscovered elsewhere. } 4...
Nf6 5. O-O O-O
{ The Tabiya − this position can arise by a multitude of move orders, and while we're not worried about White not playing  6.c4  transposing back intoPart 1, it is of course important to have a road map for the @@StartBracket@@many, sooo many@@EndBracket@@ little moves White could try here. }
6. h3 { Not a bad move but, of course, it is unlikely to refute the opening. }
6... a5
{ 6...c6  is also quite okay, with  ideas of simply developing with ...Bf5 and ...Nbd7, while also discouraging White from c4. }
7. c4 dxc4
{ 7...c6?!  8.cxd5!  cxd5  9.Nc3  is definitely something to be avoided. } 8.
Na3 Nc6 9. Nxc4
{ This is a well-known position of the normal Symmetrical Grünfeld, with h3 and ...a5 added on. I think ...a5 is by far the more useful move. }
9... a4
{ White would normally play b3 and Bb2 next, and stopping it is quite useful. }
10. Re1 Be6 11. Nce5 Nxe5
{ 11...Bd5  is also fine, but it does give White some vague hopes, while the text move is, I believe, just a forced draw, as weird as that might sound on move  11. }
12. dxe5 Nd7 13. Bf4 c6
{ The position is instantly very nice for us − the Bg2 has been neutralized and e5 is a target. }
*

