{ 6...c6  is also quite okay, with  ideas of simply developing with ...Bf5 and ...Nbd7, while also discouraging White from c4. }
7. c4 dxc4
{ 7...c6?!  8.cxd5!  cxd5  9.Nc3  is definitely something to be avoided. } 8.
Na3 Nc6 9. Nxc4
{ This is a well-known position of the normal Symmetrical Grünfeld, with h3 and ...a5 added on. I think ...a5 is by far the more useful move. }
9... a4
{ White would normally play b3 and Bb2 next, and stopping it is quite useful. }
10. Re1 Be6 11. Nce5 Nxe5
{ 11...Bd5  is also fine, but it does give White some vague hopes, while the text move is, I believe, just a forced draw, as weird as that might sound on move  11. }
12. dxe5 Nd7 13. Ng5
{ The critical test. White opens the long diagonal and simultaneously attacks our bishop on e6. }
13... Nxe5 14. Nxe6 Qxd1 15. Rxd1 fxe6 16. Bxb7 Rfd8
{ Fighting for the d-file is crucial. } 17. Re1 Rab8
{ The position is excellent for Black. } *

