[Result "*"]

1. b3 e5 { Let's play in the center and show them how it's done. } 2. Bb2 Nc6
3. c4
{ I assume by this point most of the 1.b3 games you're likely to encounter will be against the hard-core #Cowboys, so we're making the 3.c4 lines central here. In the past,  3.e3  was much more prevalent, though. }
3... Nge7
{ I think this is a little bit more flexible than  3...Nf6  , but in most cases, it will all come to the same. }
4. e3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. a3
{ This is what the #cowboys are doing @@StartBracket@@I think?@@EndBracket@@. There's a wide choice of very good ideas but I like the setup Alexander Grischuk showed. }
6... Be6 7. Bb5
{ There's maaaybe an argument for going in with 7.Bb5 since playing slowly won't work too well. }
7... Qg5
{ More ambitious than  7...f6  8.Ne2  Qd6  as in Mamedyarov-Giri, chess24.com 2021, but that is also very playable. }
8. Nf3 Qxg2 9. Rg1 Qh3 10. Rg3 Qh6 11. Nxe5 Bd6
{ We have a very odd horribly sharp position in which the machine suggests we're maybe a touch better. }
12. Qf3
{ If White plays  12.Nxc6  we can answer with  12...Bxg3  and a potential discovered check is harmless. }
12... O-O-O { Getting the king out of center. } 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. Nxc6 Qxh2
{ Removing support from Rg3 and dodging Bxg7. } 15. Nxd8 Rxd8
{ We are an exchange down but the position offers us great dynamic possibilities of which  16.Rg2  Qh1+  17.Ke2  Re8!  threatening  ...Nf4+, exf4, ...Bc4 mate, is a great example. The fact the White still has the entire Q-side undeveloped helps a great deal, too. }
*

