[Result "*"]

1. b3 e5 { Let's play in the center and show them how it's done. } 2. Bb2 Nc6
3. c4
{ I assume by this point most of the 1.b3 games you're likely to encounter will be against the hard-core #Cowboys, so we're making the 3.c4 lines central here. In the past,  3.e3  was much more prevalent, though. }
3... Nge7
{ I think this is a little bit more flexible than  3...Nf6  , but in most cases, it will all come to the same. }
4. e3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. a3
{ This is what the #cowboys are doing @@StartBracket@@I think?@@EndBracket@@. There's a wide choice of very good ideas but I like the setup Alexander Grischuk showed. }
6... Be6 7. Nf3 f6 8. Qc2 Qd7
{ We want to castle Q-side and then start on the ...g5-g4 plans. } 9. b4
{ White needs to be quick and this move creates the idea of b5 and d4. } 9...
O-O-O
{ I like this simple move best, but you can also play the alternative  9...Bf5  . }
10. Nc3 { Too slow. } 10... Nxc3 11. Bxc3 Kb8
{ Not committing to ...g5 yet makes it easier to deal with d2-d4 later.  11...g5  12.b5   12.h3?!  Kb8  13.Be2  Rg8  was very good for Black in Ivanisevic-Grischuk, chess.com 2021.  12...Ne7  13.d4  g4  14.Nd2  is quite unclear. Note that @@StartFEN@@2kr1b1r/pppqn2p/4bp2/1P2p1p1/3P4/P1B1PN2/2Q2PPP/R3KB1R b KQ - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...e4?  14.Nxg5!  fxg5  15.d5  is wrong, and  illustrates why keeping that pawn on g7 for a while yet might be stronger. }
12. b5 Ne7 13. d4 e4 14. Nd2
{ 14.Qxe4??  Bf5  15.Qh4  Ng6  16.Qg3  Bd6  would be a mistake. } 14... f5
{ A double-edged middlegame position but with both ...Nd5 and ...Bd6 coming, we have good central control @@StartBracket@@reminiscent of a reversed French@@EndBracket@@. }
*

