[White "30. Bird 1.f4"]
[Black "Bird 1.f4 − 3.e3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. f4
{ The fabled reversed Dutch. Turns out even a tempo-up Dutch is still not great, who could have known. }
1... d5 2. Nf3 c5 3. e3 g6 4. d4
{ The Stonewall is very solid, of course, but it's hardly going to scare us. }
4... Bg7 5. Bd3 Nh6
{ I like the plan of getting this knight to f5 and then d6 as soon as possible. }
6. c3 O-O 7. Nbd2 Qc7
{ A useful move often made with reversed colors as well in the Stonewall. One of the ideas is to connect the rooks, the other is to sometimes be able to take on d4 and force White to recapture with the c-pawn since f4 would be hanging in case of exd4. }
8. O-O Nf5
{ This is an example where  8...cxd4  9.exd4  Qxf4  is very dangerous for Black. White continues  10.Ne5  and has very serious compensation. }
9. Qe2 Nd6 { The game is very playable for us. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "30. Bird 1.f4"]
[Black "Bird 1.f4 − 3.e3 #2 | Alternative 8...Bf5"]
[Result "*"]

1. f4
{ The fabled reversed Dutch. Turns out even a tempo-up Dutch is still not great, who could have known. }
1... d5 2. Nf3 c5 3. e3 g6 4. d4
{ The Stonewall is very solid, of course, but it's hardly going to scare us. }
4... Bg7 5. Bd3 Nh6
{ I like the plan of getting this knight to f5 and then d6 as soon as possible. }
6. c3 O-O 7. Nbd2 Qc7
{ A useful move often made with reversed colors as well in the Stonewall. One of the ideas is to connect the rooks, the other is to sometimes be able to take on d4 and force White to recapture with the c-pawn since f4 would be hanging in case of exd4. }
8. O-O Bf5 { This is also a typical idea you should be aware of. } 9. Be2 Ng4
10. Nb3 c4 11. h3 Nf6 12. Nbd2 Nc6 { The fight is very sharp and unclear. } *

