1. f4
{ The fabled reversed Dutch. Turns out even a tempo-up Dutch is still not great, who could have known. }
1... d5 2. Nf3 c5 3. g3
{ Most people play the Bird with the intention of playing the tempo up Leningrad, but we'll take a brief look at the other options, too. }
3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O Nc6 6. d3
{ 6.c3  doesn't have any independent value:  6...Nf6  7.d3  O-O  will transpose to the6.d3 variation. }
6... Nf6 7. Nbd2
{ This is just wrong because White will constantly worry about ...Ng4-e3 ideas. }
7... O-O 8. c3
{ 8.e4?  Ng4!  is simply bad for White.  There is no good way of countering the ...Ne3 threat  since  9.Re1  c4!  prepares  a deadly check on b6,  while @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2ppbp/2n3p1/2pp4/4PPn1/3P1NP1/PPPN2BP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Qe2  Nd4!  10.Nxd4  Bxd4+  11.Kh1  Ne3  wins the house. }
8... d4 { We're quite happy with how the opening turned out. } *

