1. f4
{ The fabled reversed Dutch. Turns out even a tempo-up Dutch is still not great, who could have known. }
1... d5 2. Nf3 c5 3. g3
{ Most people play the Bird with the intention of playing the tempo up Leningrad, but we'll take a brief look at the other options, too. }
3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O Nc6 6. d3
{ 6.c3  doesn't have any independent value:  6...Nf6  7.d3  O-O  will transpose to the6.d3 variation. }
6... Nf6 7. Nc3 d4 8. Na4 b6
{ This is an interesting and completely new sacrificial idea. } 9. Ne5 Nxe5 10.
Bxa8 Neg4 11. Bc6+ Kf8
{ We're a full exchange down, but the Na4 is completely out of play, and our attack on the K-side is quite fast, with ...h5-h4 coming soon. }
12. h3 Ne3 13. Bxe3 dxe3 14. Bg2 e5
{ It's time to remind White that control over the dark squares is missing. }
15. Nc3 Nh5 16. Qe1 Rg8
{ It is too early for  16...exf4  17.g4!  ,  but with the rook on g8 we're now threatening to take  @@StartFEN@@2bq1kr1/p4pbp/1p4p1/2p1p2n/5P2/2NPp1PP/PPP1P1B1/R3QRK1 b - - 4 17@@EndFEN@@  17...exf4  and meet  18.g4  with  18...Bxc3  and ...Qg5, because gxh5, ...gxh5 will open up the g-file for our rook with decisive results. }
*

