1. f4
{ The fabled reversed Dutch. Turns out even a tempo-up Dutch is still not great, who could have known. }
1... d5 2. Nf3 c5 3. g3
{ Most people play the Bird with the intention of playing the tempo up Leningrad, but we'll take a brief look at the other options, too. }
3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O Nc6 6. d3
{ 6.c3  doesn't have any independent value:  6...Nf6  7.d3  O-O  will transpose to the6.d3 variation. }
6... Nf6 7. c3 O-O 8. Na3 Rb8
{ In some cases, we'll happily play ...b5, but this move is generally useful. }
9. Nc2 b6 { Finishing development first. } 10. Qe1
{ 10.Bd2  prepares  the b2-b4 advance, but it is something we are not afraid of. After  10...Bb7  11.b4  e6⩱  and Black is simply slightly better.  11...cxb4  should be avoided as it gives White control over the important d4-square. }
10... Bb7
{ Our plan here is to push for the ...e5 break, but the most immediate idea is to play ...d4. }
11. e4 dxe4 12. dxe4 Qd3 13. Qd2
{ This preserves the e4-pawn but we're fine regardless. } 13... Qxd2 14. Nxd2
e5 { Physically preventing e4-e5. } 15. f5 Na5
{ We're even a bit better in this endgame. } *

